   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
10	
11	DOCUMENTATION = '''
12	---
13	module: apt_key
14	author:
15	- Jayson Vantuyl (@jvantuyl)
16	version_added: "1.0"
17	short_description: Add or remove an apt key
18	description:
19	    - Add or remove an I(apt) key, optionally downloading it.
20	extends_documentation_fragment: action_common_attributes
21	attributes:
22	    check_mode:
23	        support: full
24	    diff_mode:
25	        support: none
26	    platform:
27	        platforms: debian
28	notes:
29	    - The C(apt-key) command used by this module has been deprecated. See the L(Debian wiki,https://wiki.debian.org/DebianRepository/UseThirdParty) for details.
30	      This module is kept for backwards compatibility for systems that still use C(apt-key) as the main way to manage apt repository keys.
31	    - As a sanity check, downloaded key id must match the one specified.
32	    - "Use full fingerprint (40 characters) key ids to avoid key collisions.
33	      To generate a full-fingerprint imported key: C(apt-key adv --list-public-keys --with-fingerprint --with-colons)."
34	    - If you specify both the key O(id) and the O(url) with O(state=present), the task can verify or add the key as needed.
35	    - Adding a new key requires an apt cache update (e.g. using the M(ansible.builtin.apt) module's C(update_cache) option).
36	requirements:
37	    - gpg
38	seealso:
39	  - module: ansible.builtin.deb822_repository
40	options:
41	    id:
42	        description:
43	            - The identifier of the key.
44	            - Including this allows check mode to correctly report the changed state.
45	            - If specifying a subkey's id be aware that apt-key does not understand how to remove keys via a subkey id. Specify the primary key's id instead.
46	            - This parameter is required when O(state) is set to V(absent).
47	        type: str
48	    data:
49	        description:
50	            - The keyfile contents to add to the keyring.
51	        type: str
52	    file:
53	        description:
54	            - The path to a keyfile on the remote server to add to the keyring.
55	        type: path
56	    keyring:
57	        description:
58	            - The full path to specific keyring file in C(/etc/apt/trusted.gpg.d/).
59	        type: path
60	        version_added: "1.3"
61	    url:
62	        description:
63	            - The URL to retrieve key from.
64	        type: str
65	    keyserver:
66	        description:
67	            - The keyserver to retrieve key from.
68	        type: str
69	        version_added: "1.6"
70	    state:
71	        description:
72	            - Ensures that the key is present (added) or absent (revoked).
73	        type: str
74	        choices: [ absent, present ]
75	        default: present
76	    validate_certs:
77	        description:
78	            - If V(false), SSL certificates for the target url will not be validated. This should only be used
79	              on personally controlled sites using self-signed certificates.
80	        type: bool
81	        default: 'yes'
82	'''

11	DOCUMENTATION = r'''
12	---
13	module: assemble
14	short_description: Assemble configuration files from fragments
15	description:
16	- Assembles a configuration file from fragments.
17	- Often a particular program will take a single configuration file and does not support a
18	  C(conf.d) style structure where it is easy to build up the configuration
19	  from multiple sources. M(ansible.builtin.assemble) will take a directory of files that can be
20	  local or have already been transferred to the system, and concatenate them
21	  together to produce a destination file.
22	- Files are assembled in string sorting order.
23	- Puppet calls this idea I(fragments).
24	version_added: '0.5'
25	options:
26	  src:
27	    description:
28	    - An already existing directory full of source files.
29	    type: path
30	    required: true
31	  dest:
32	    description:
33	    - A file to create using the concatenation of all of the source files.
34	    type: path
35	    required: true
36	  backup:
37	    description:
38	    - Create a backup file (if V(true)), including the timestamp information so
39	      you can get the original file back if you somehow clobbered it
40	      incorrectly.
41	    type: bool
42	    default: no
43	  delimiter:
44	    description:
45	    - A delimiter to separate the file contents.
46	    type: str
47	    version_added: '1.4'
48	  remote_src:
49	    description:
50	    - If V(false), it will search for src at originating/master machine.
51	    - If V(true), it will go to the remote/target machine for the src.
52	    type: bool
53	    default: yes
54	    version_added: '1.4'
55	  regexp:
56	    description:
57	    - Assemble files only if the given regular expression matches the filename.
58	    - If not set, all files are assembled.
59	    - Every V(\\) (backslash) must be escaped as V(\\\\) to comply to YAML syntax.
60	    - Uses L(Python regular expressions,https://docs.python.org/3/library/re.html).
61	    type: str
62	  ignore_hidden:
63	    description:
64	    - A boolean that controls if files that start with a C(.) will be included or not.
65	    type: bool
66	    default: no
67	    version_added: '2.0'
68	  validate:
69	    description:
70	    - The validation command to run before copying into place.
71	    - The path to the file to validate is passed in by C(%s) which must be present as in the sshd example below.
72	    - The command is passed securely so shell features like expansion and pipes won't work.
73	    type: str
74	    version_added: '2.0'
75	attributes:
76	    action:
77	      support: full
78	    async:
79	      support: none
80	    bypass_host_loop:
81	      support: none
82	    check_mode:
83	      support: none
84	    diff_mode:
85	      support: full
86	    platform:
87	      platforms: posix
88	    safe_file_operations:
89	      support: full
90	    vault:
91	      support: full
92	      version_added: '2.2'
93	seealso:
94	- module: ansible.builtin.copy
95	- module: ansible.builtin.template
96	- module: ansible.windows.win_copy
97	author:
98	- Stephen Fromm (@sfromm)
99	extends_documentation_fragment:
100	    - action_common_attributes
101	    - action_common_attributes.flow
102	    - action_common_attributes.files
103	    - decrypt
104	    - files
105	'''

   Severity: Medium   Confidence: Medium
   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/ansible_core-2.18.4/ansible_core-2.18.4/lib/ansible/modules/command.py:10
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
9	
10	DOCUMENTATION = r'''
11	---
12	module: command
13	short_description: Execute commands on targets
14	version_added: historical
15	description:
16	     - The M(ansible.builtin.command) module takes the command name followed by a list of space-delimited arguments.
17	     - The given command will be executed on all selected nodes.
18	     - The command(s) will not be processed through the shell, so operations like C("*"), C("<"), C(">"), C("|"), C(";") and C("&") will not work.
19	       Also, environment variables are resolved via Python, not shell, see O(expand_argument_vars) and are left unchanged if not matched.
20	       Use the M(ansible.builtin.shell) module if you need these features.
21	     - To create C(command) tasks that are easier to read than the ones using space-delimited arguments,
22	       pass parameters using the C(args) L(task keyword,https://docs.ansible.com/ansible/latest/reference_appendices/playbooks_keywords.html#task)
23	       or use O(cmd) parameter.
24	     - Either a free form command or O(cmd) parameter is required, see the examples.
25	     - For Windows targets, use the M(ansible.windows.win_command) module instead.
26	extends_documentation_fragment:
27	    - action_common_attributes
28	    - action_common_attributes.raw
29	attributes:
30	    check_mode:
31	        details: while the command itself is arbitrary and cannot be subject to the check mode semantics it adds O(creates)/O(removes) options as a workaround
32	        support: partial
33	    diff_mode:
34	        support: none
35	    platform:
36	      support: full
37	      platforms: posix
38	    raw:
39	      support: full
40	options:
41	  expand_argument_vars:
42	    description:
43	      - Expands the arguments that are variables, for example C($HOME) will be expanded before being passed to the command to run.
44	      - If a variable is not matched, it is left unchanged, unlike shell substitution which would remove it.
45	      - Set to V(false) to disable expansion and treat the value as a literal argument.
46	    type: bool
47	    default: true
48	    version_added: "2.16"
49	  free_form:
50	    description:
51	      - The command module takes a free form string as a command to run.
52	      - There is no actual parameter named C(free_form).
53	  cmd:
54	    type: str
55	    description:
56	      - The command to run.
57	  argv:
58	    type: list
59	    elements: str
60	    description:
61	      - Passes the command as a list rather than a string.
62	      - Use O(argv) to avoid quoting values that would otherwise be interpreted incorrectly (for example "user name").
63	      - Only the string (free form) or the list (argv) form can be provided, not both.  One or the other must be provided.
64	    version_added: "2.6"
65	  creates:
66	    type: path
67	    description:
68	      - A filename or (since 2.0) glob pattern. If a matching file already exists, this step B(will not) be run.
69	      - This is checked before O(removes) is checked.
70	  removes:
71	    type: path
72	    description:
73	      - A filename or (since 2.0) glob pattern. If a matching file exists, this step B(will) be run.
74	      - This is checked after O(creates) is checked.
75	    version_added: "0.8"
76	  chdir:
77	    type: path
78	    description:
79	      - Change into this directory before running the command.
80	    version_added: "0.6"
81	  stdin:
82	    description:
83	      - Set the stdin of the command directly to the specified value.
84	    type: str
85	    version_added: "2.4"
86	  stdin_add_newline:
87	    type: bool
88	    default: yes
89	    description:
90	      - If set to V(true), append a newline to stdin data.
91	    version_added: "2.8"
92	  strip_empty_ends:
93	    description:
94	      - Strip empty lines from the end of stdout/stderr in result.
95	    version_added: "2.8"
96	    type: bool
97	    default: yes
98	notes:
99	    -  If you want to run a command through the shell (say you are using C(<), C(>), C(|), and so on),
100	       you actually want the M(ansible.builtin.shell) module instead.
101	       Parsing shell metacharacters can lead to unexpected commands being executed if quoting is not done correctly so it is more secure to
102	       use the M(ansible.builtin.command) module when possible.
103	    -  O(creates), O(removes), and O(chdir) can be specified after the command.
104	       For instance, if you only want to run a command if a certain file does not exist, use this.
105	    -  Check mode is supported when passing O(creates) or O(removes). If running in check mode and either of these are specified, the module will
106	       check for the existence of the file and report the correct changed status. If these are not supplied, the task will be skipped.
107	    -  The O(ignore:executable) parameter is removed since version 2.4. If you have a need for this parameter, use the M(ansible.builtin.shell) module instead.
108	    -  For Windows targets, use the M(ansible.windows.win_command) module instead.
109	    -  For rebooting systems, use the M(ansible.builtin.reboot) or M(ansible.windows.win_reboot) module.
110	    -  If the command returns non UTF-8 data, it must be encoded to avoid issues. This may necessitate using M(ansible.builtin.shell) so the output
111	       can be piped through C(base64).
112	seealso:
113	- module: ansible.builtin.raw
114	- module: ansible.builtin.script
115	- module: ansible.builtin.shell
116	- module: ansible.windows.win_command
117	author:
118	    - Ansible Core Team
119	    - Michael DeHaan
120	'''

33	  name:
34	    description:
35	      - "A package name or package specifier with version, like C(name-1.0).
36	        When using state=latest, this can be '*' which means run: dnf -y update.
37	        You can also pass a url or a local path to an rpm file.
38	        To operate on several packages this can accept a comma separated string of packages or a list of packages."
39	      - Comparison operators for package version are valid here C(>), C(<), C(>=), C(<=). Example - C(name >= 1.0).
40	        Spaces around the operator are required.
41	      - You can also pass an absolute path for a binary which is provided by the package to install.
42	        See examples for more information.

53	    type: str
54	
55	  state:
56	    description:
57	      - Whether to install (V(present), V(latest)), or remove (V(absent)) a package.
58	      - Default is V(None), however in effect the default action is V(present) unless the O(autoremove=true),
59	        then V(absent) is inferred.
60	    choices: ['absent', 'present', 'installed', 'removed', 'latest']
61	    type: str
62

66	        These repos will not persist beyond the transaction.
67	        When specifying multiple repos, separate them with a ",".

206	        behave in a non-idempotent way. The task could end up with a set

256	      - Since ansible-core 2.17 the default value is set by the operating system distribution.
257	    required: false
258	    type: bool
259	    version_added: "2.11"
260	  best:
261	    description:
262	      - When set to V(true), either use a package with the highest version available or fail.
263	      - When set to V(false), if the latest version cannot be installed go with the lower version.
264	      - Default is set by the operating system distribution.
265	    required: false
266	    type: bool
267	    version_added: "2.17"
268	  cacheonly:
269	    description:
270	      - Tells dnf to run entirely from system cache; does not download or update metadata.
271	    type: bool
272	    default: "no"
273	    version_added: "2.12"
274	extends_documentation_fragment:
275	- action_common_attributes
276	- action_common_attributes.flow
277	attributes:
278	    action:
279	        details: dnf has 2 action plugins that use it under the hood, M(ansible.builtin.dnf) and M(ansible.builtin.package).
280	        support: partial
281	    async:
282	        support: none
283	    bypass_host_loop:
284	        support: none
285	    check_mode:
286	        support: full
287	    diff_mode:
288	        support: full
289	    platform:
290	        platforms: rhel
291	notes:
292	  - When used with a C(loop:) each package will be processed individually, it is much more efficient to pass the list directly to the O(name) option.
293	  - Group removal doesn't work if the group was installed with Ansible because
294	    upstream dnf's API doesn't properly mark groups as installed, therefore upon
295	    removal the module is unable to detect that the group is installed
296	    U(https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1620324).
297	  - While O(use_backend=yum) and the ability to call the action plugin as
298	    M(ansible.builtin.yum) are provided for syntax compatibility, the YUM
299	    backend was removed in ansible-core 2.17 because the required libraries are
300	    not available for any supported version of Python. If you rely on this
301	    functionality, use an older version of Ansible.
302	requirements:
303	  - python3-dnf
304	author:
305	  - Igor Gnatenko (@ignatenkobrain) <i.gnatenko.brain@gmail.com>
306	  - Cristian van Ee (@DJMuggs) <cristian at cvee.org>
307	  - Berend De Schouwer (@berenddeschouwer)
308	  - Adam Miller (@maxamillion) <admiller@redhat.com>

10	---
11	module: expect
12	version_added: '2.0'
13	short_description: Executes a command and responds to prompts
14	description:
15	     - The M(ansible.builtin.expect) module executes a command and responds to prompts.
16	     - The given command will be executed on all selected nodes. It will not be
17	       processed through the shell, so variables like C($HOME) and operations
18	       like C("<"), C(">"), C("|"), and C("&") will not work.
19	options:
20	  command:
21	    description:
22	      - The command module takes command to run.
23	    required: true
24	    type: str
25	  creates:
26	    type: path
27	    description:
28	      - A filename, when it already exists, this step will B(not) be run.
29	  removes:
30	    type: path
31	    description:
32	      - A filename, when it does not exist, this step will B(not) be run.
33	  chdir:
34	    type: path
35	    description:
36	      - Change into this directory before running the command.
37	  responses:
38	    type: dict
39	    description:
40	      - Mapping of prompt regular expressions and corresponding answer(s).
41	      - Each key in O(responses) is a Python regex U(https://docs.python.org/3/library/re.html#regular-expression-syntax).
42	      - The value of each key is a string or list of strings.
43	        If the value is a string and the prompt is encountered multiple times, the answer will be repeated.
44	        Provide the value as a list to give different answers for successive matches.
45	    required: true
46	  timeout:
47	    type: raw
48	    description:
49	      - Amount of time in seconds to wait for the expected strings. Use
50	        V(null) to disable timeout.
51	    default: 30
52	  echo:
53	    description:
54	      - Whether or not to echo out your response strings.
55	    default: false
56	    type: bool
57	requirements:
58	  - python >= 2.6
59	  - pexpect >= 3.3
60	extends_documentation_fragment: action_common_attributes
61	attributes:
62	    check_mode:
63	        support: none
64	    diff_mode:
65	        support: none
66	    platform:
67	        support: full
68	        platforms: posix
69	notes:
70	  - If you want to run a command through the shell (say you are using C(<),
71	    C(>), C(|), and so on), you must specify a shell in the command such as
72	    C(/bin/bash -c "/path/to/something | grep else").
73	  - Case insensitive searches are indicated with a prefix of C((?i)).
74	  - The C(pexpect) library used by this module operates with a search window
75	    of 2000 bytes, and does not use a multiline regex match. To perform a
76	    start of line bound match, use a pattern like C((?m)^pattern).
77	  - The M(ansible.builtin.expect) module is designed for simple scenarios.
78	    For more complex needs, consider the use of expect code with the M(ansible.builtin.shell)
79	    or M(ansible.builtin.script) modules. (An example is part of the M(ansible.builtin.shell) module documentation).
80	  - If the command returns non UTF-8 data, it must be encoded to avoid issues. One option is to pipe
81	    the output through C(base64).

84	- module: ansible.builtin.shell

10	---
11	module: get_url
12	short_description: Downloads files from HTTP, HTTPS, or FTP to node
13	description:
14	     - Downloads files from HTTP, HTTPS, or FTP to the remote server. The remote
15	       server I(must) have direct access to the remote resource.
16	     - By default, if an environment variable E(<protocol>_proxy) is set on
17	       the target host, requests will be sent through that proxy. This
18	       behaviour can be overridden by setting a variable for this task
19	       (see R(setting the environment,playbooks_environment)),
20	       or by using the use_proxy option.
21	     - HTTP redirects can redirect from HTTP to HTTPS so you should be sure that
22	       your proxy environment for both protocols is correct.
23	     - From Ansible 2.4 when run with C(--check), it will do a HEAD request to validate the URL but
24	       will not download the entire file or verify it against hashes and will report incorrect changed status.
25	     - For Windows targets, use the M(ansible.windows.win_get_url) module instead.
26	version_added: '0.6'
27	options:
28	  ciphers:
29	    description:
30	      - SSL/TLS Ciphers to use for the request.
31	      - 'When a list is provided, all ciphers are joined in order with C(:).'
32	      - See the L(OpenSSL Cipher List Format,https://www.openssl.org/docs/manmaster/man1/openssl-ciphers.html#CIPHER-LIST-FORMAT)
33	        for more details.
34	      - The available ciphers is dependent on the Python and OpenSSL/LibreSSL versions.
35	    type: list
36	    elements: str
37	    version_added: '2.14'
38	  decompress:
39	    description:
40	      - Whether to attempt to decompress gzip content-encoded responses.
41	    type: bool
42	    default: true
43	    version_added: '2.14'
44	  url:

46	      - HTTP, HTTPS, or FTP URL in the form C((http|https|ftp)://[user[:pass]]@host.domain[:port]/path).
47	    type: str
48	    required: true
49	  dest:
50	    description:
51	      - Absolute path of where to download the file to.
52	      - If O(dest) is a directory, either the server provided filename or, if
53	        none provided, the base name of the URL on the remote server will be
54	        used. If a directory, O(force) has no effect.
55	      - If O(dest) is a directory, the file will always be downloaded
56	        (regardless of the O(force) and O(checksum) option), but
57	        replaced only if the contents changed.
58	    type: path
59	    required: true
60	  tmp_dest:
61	    description:
62	      - Absolute path of where temporary file is downloaded to.
63	      - When run on Ansible 2.5 or greater, path defaults to ansible's C(remote_tmp) setting.
64	      - When run on Ansible prior to 2.5, it defaults to E(TMPDIR), E(TEMP) or E(TMP) env variables or a platform specific value.
65	      - U(https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html#tempfile.tempdir).
66	    type: path
67	    version_added: '2.1'
68	  force:
69	    description:
70	      - If V(true) and O(dest) is not a directory, will download the file every
71	        time and replace the file if the contents change. If V(false), the file
72	        will only be downloaded if the destination does not exist. Generally
73	        should be V(true) only for small local files.
74	      - Prior to 0.6, this module behaved as if V(true) was the default.
75	    type: bool
76	    default: no
77	    version_added: '0.7'
78	  backup:
79	    description:
80	      - Create a backup file including the timestamp information so you can get
81	        the original file back if you somehow clobbered it incorrectly.
82	    type: bool
83	    default: no
84	    version_added: '2.1'
85	  checksum:
86	    description:
87	      - 'If a checksum is passed to this parameter, the digest of the
88	        destination file will be calculated after it is downloaded to ensure
89	        its integrity and verify that the transfer completed successfully.
90	        Format: <algorithm>:<checksum|url>, for example C(checksum="sha256:D98291AC[...]B6DC7B97",
91	        C(checksum="sha256:http://example.com/path/sha256sum.txt").'
92	      - If you worry about portability, only the sha1 algorithm is available
93	        on all platforms and python versions.
94	      - The Python C(hashlib) module is responsible for providing the available algorithms.
95	        The choices vary based on Python version and OpenSSL version.
96	      - On systems running in FIPS compliant mode, the C(md5) algorithm may be unavailable.
97	      - Additionally, if a checksum is passed to this parameter, and the file exist under
98	        the O(dest) location, the C(destination_checksum) would be calculated, and if
99	        checksum equals C(destination_checksum), the file download would be skipped
100	        (unless O(force=true)). If the checksum does not equal C(destination_checksum),
101	        the destination file is deleted.
102	      - If the checksum URL requires username and password, O(url_username) and O(url_password) are used
103	        to download the checksum file.
104	    type: str
105	    default: ''
106	    version_added: "2.0"
107	  use_proxy:
108	    description:
109	      - if V(false), it will not use a proxy, even if one is defined in
110	        an environment variable on the target hosts.
111	    type: bool
112	    default: yes
113	  validate_certs:
114	    description:
115	      - If V(false), SSL certificates will not be validated.
116	      - This should only be used on personally controlled sites using self-signed certificates.
117	    type: bool
118	    default: yes
119	  timeout:
120	    description:
121	      - Timeout in seconds for URL request.
122	    type: int
123	    default: 10
124	    version_added: '1.8'
125	  headers:
126	    description:
127	        - Add custom HTTP headers to a request in hash/dict format.
128	        - The hash/dict format was added in Ansible 2.6.
129	        - Previous versions used a C("key:value,key:value") string format.
130	        - The C("key:value,key:value") string format is deprecated and has been removed in version 2.10.
131	    type: dict
132	    version_added: '2.0'
133	  url_username:
134	    description:
135	      - The username for use in HTTP basic authentication.
136	      - This parameter can be used without O(url_password) for sites that allow empty passwords.
137	      - Since version 2.8 you can also use the O(username) alias for this option.
138	    type: str
139	    aliases: ['username']
140	    version_added: '1.6'
141	  url_password:
142	    description:
143	        - The password for use in HTTP basic authentication.
144	        - If the O(url_username) parameter is not specified, the O(url_password) parameter will not be used.
145	        - Since version 2.8 you can also use the O(password) alias for this option.
146	    type: str
147	    aliases: ['password']
148	    version_added: '1.6'
149	  force_basic_auth:
150	    description:
151	      - Force the sending of the Basic authentication header upon initial request.
152	      - httplib2, the library used by the uri module only sends authentication information when a webservice
153	        responds to an initial request with a 401 status. Since some basic auth services do not properly
154	        send a 401, logins will fail.
155	    type: bool
156	    default: no
157	    version_added: '2.0'
158	  client_cert:
159	    description:
160	      - PEM formatted certificate chain file to be used for SSL client authentication.
161	      - This file can also include the key as well, and if the key is included, O(client_key) is not required.
162	    type: path
163	    version_added: '2.4'
164	  client_key:
165	    description:
166	      - PEM formatted file that contains your private key to be used for SSL client authentication.
167	      - If O(client_cert) contains both the certificate and key, this option is not required.
168	    type: path
169	    version_added: '2.4'
170	  http_agent:
171	    description:
172	      - Header to identify as, generally appears in web server logs.
173	    type: str
174	    default: ansible-httpget
175	  unredirected_headers:
176	    description:
177	      - A list of header names that will not be sent on subsequent redirected requests. This list is case
178	        insensitive. By default all headers will be redirected. In some cases it may be beneficial to list
179	        headers such as C(Authorization) here to avoid potential credential exposure.
180	    default: []
181	    type: list
182	    elements: str
183	    version_added: '2.12'
184	  use_gssapi:
185	    description:
186	      - Use GSSAPI to perform the authentication, typically this is for Kerberos or Kerberos through Negotiate
187	        authentication.
188	      - Requires the Python library L(gssapi,https://github.com/pythongssapi/python-gssapi) to be installed.
189	      - Credentials for GSSAPI can be specified with O(url_username)/O(url_password) or with the GSSAPI env var
190	        E(KRB5CCNAME) that specified a custom Kerberos credential cache.
191	      - NTLM authentication is I(not) supported even if the GSSAPI mech for NTLM has been installed.
192	    type: bool
193	    default: no
194	    version_added: '2.11'
195	  use_netrc:
196	    description:
197	      - Determining whether to use credentials from C(~/.netrc) file.
198	      - By default C(.netrc) is used with Basic authentication headers.
199	      - When V(false), C(.netrc) credentials are ignored.
200	    type: bool
201	    default: true
202	    version_added: '2.14'
203	# informational: requirements for nodes
204	extends_documentation_fragment:
205	    - files
206	    - action_common_attributes
207	attributes:
208	    check_mode:
209	        details: the changed status will reflect comparison to an empty source file
210	        support: partial
211	    diff_mode:
212	        support: none
213	    platform:
214	        platforms: posix
215	notes:
216	     - For Windows targets, use the M(ansible.windows.win_get_url) module instead.
217	seealso:
218	- module: ansible.builtin.uri
219	- module: ansible.windows.win_get_url
220	author:
221	- Jan-Piet Mens (@jpmens)
222	'''

>> Issue: [B824:url_found] url_found
   Severity: Medium   Confidence: Medium
   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/ansible_core-2.18.4/ansible_core-2.18.4/lib/ansible/modules/lineinfile.py:11
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
10	
11	DOCUMENTATION = r'''
12	---
13	module: lineinfile
14	short_description: Manage lines in text files
15	description:
16	  - This module ensures a particular line is in a file, or replace an
17	    existing line using a back-referenced regular expression.
18	  - This is primarily useful when you want to change a single line in a file only.
19	  - See the M(ansible.builtin.replace) module if you want to change multiple, similar lines
20	    or check M(ansible.builtin.blockinfile) if you want to insert/update/remove a block of lines in a file.
21	    For other cases, see the M(ansible.builtin.copy) or M(ansible.builtin.template) modules.
22	version_added: "0.7"
23	options:
24	  path:
25	    description:
26	      - The file to modify.
27	      - Before Ansible 2.3 this option was only usable as O(dest), O(destfile) and O(name).
28	    type: path
29	    required: true
30	    aliases: [ dest, destfile, name ]
31	  regexp:
32	    description:
33	      - The regular expression to look for in every line of the file.
34	      - For O(state=present), the pattern to replace if found. Only the last line found will be replaced.
35	      - For O(state=absent), the pattern of the line(s) to remove.
36	      - If the regular expression is not matched, the line will be
37	        added to the file in keeping with O(insertbefore) or O(insertafter)
38	        settings.
39	      - When modifying a line the regexp should typically match both the initial state of
40	        the line as well as its state after replacement by O(line) to ensure idempotence.
41	      - Uses Python regular expressions. See U(https://docs.python.org/3/library/re.html).
42	    type: str
43	    aliases: [ regex ]
44	    version_added: '1.7'
45	  search_string:
46	    description:
47	      - The literal string to look for in every line of the file. This does not have to match the entire line.
48	      - For O(state=present), the line to replace if the string is found in the file. Only the last line found will be replaced.
49	      - For O(state=absent), the line(s) to remove if the string is in the line.
50	      - If the literal expression is not matched, the line will be
51	        added to the file in keeping with O(insertbefore) or O(insertafter)
52	        settings.
53	      - Mutually exclusive with O(backrefs) and O(regexp).
54	    type: str
55	    version_added: '2.11'
56	  state:
57	    description:
58	      - Whether the line should be there or not.
59	    type: str
60	    choices: [ absent, present ]
61	    default: present
62	  line:
63	    description:
64	      - The line to insert/replace into the file.
65	      - Required for O(state=present).
66	      - If O(backrefs) is set, may contain backreferences that will get
67	        expanded with the O(regexp) capture groups if the regexp matches.
68	    type: str
69	    aliases: [ value ]
70	  backrefs:
71	    description:
72	      - Used with O(state=present).
73	      - If set, O(line) can contain backreferences (both positional and named)
74	        that will get populated if the O(regexp) matches.
75	      - This parameter changes the operation of the module slightly;
76	        O(insertbefore) and O(insertafter) will be ignored, and if the O(regexp)
77	        does not match anywhere in the file, the file will be left unchanged.
78	      - If the O(regexp) does match, the last matching line will be replaced by
79	        the expanded line parameter.
80	      - Mutually exclusive with O(search_string).
81	    type: bool
82	    default: no
83	    version_added: "1.1"
84	  insertafter:
85	    description:
86	      - Used with O(state=present).
87	      - If specified, the line will be inserted after the last match of specified regular expression.
88	      - If the first match is required, use(firstmatch=yes).
89	      - A special value is available; V(EOF) for inserting the line at the end of the file.
90	      - If specified regular expression has no matches or no value is passed, V(EOF) will be used instead.
91	      - If O(insertbefore) is set, default value V(EOF) will be ignored.
92	      - If regular expressions are passed to both O(regexp) and O(insertafter), O(insertafter) is only honored if no match for O(regexp) is found.
93	      - May not be used with O(backrefs) or O(insertbefore).
94	    type: str
95	  insertbefore:
96	    description:
97	      - Used with O(state=present).
98	      - If specified, the line will be inserted before the last match of specified regular expression.
99	      - If the first match is required, use O(firstmatch=yes).
100	      - A value is available; V(BOF) for inserting the line at the beginning of the file.
101	      - If specified regular expression has no matches, the line will be inserted at the end of the file.
102	      - If regular expressions are passed to both O(regexp) and O(insertbefore), O(insertbefore) is only honored if no match for O(regexp) is found.
103	      - May not be used with O(backrefs) or O(insertafter).
104	    type: str
105	    version_added: "1.1"
106	  create:
107	    description:
108	      - Used with O(state=present).
109	      - If specified, the file will be created if it does not already exist.
110	      - By default it will fail if the file is missing.
111	    type: bool
112	    default: no
113	  backup:
114	    description:
115	      - Create a backup file including the timestamp information so you can
116	        get the original file back if you somehow clobbered it incorrectly.
117	    type: bool
118	    default: no
119	  firstmatch:
120	    description:
121	      - Used with O(insertafter) or O(insertbefore).
122	      - If set, O(insertafter) and O(insertbefore) will work with the first line that matches the given regular expression.
123	    type: bool
124	    default: no
125	    version_added: "2.5"
126	extends_documentation_fragment:
127	    - action_common_attributes
128	    - action_common_attributes.files
129	    - files
130	    - validate
131	attributes:
132	    check_mode:
133	        support: full
134	    diff_mode:
135	        support: full
136	    platform:
137	        platforms: posix
138	    safe_file_operations:
139	        support: full
140	    vault:
141	        support: none
142	notes:
143	  - As of Ansible 2.3, the O(dest) option has been changed to O(path) as default, but O(dest) still works as well.
144	seealso:
145	- module: ansible.builtin.blockinfile
146	- module: ansible.builtin.copy
147	- module: ansible.builtin.file
148	- module: ansible.builtin.replace
149	- module: ansible.builtin.template
150	- module: community.windows.win_lineinfile
151	author:
152	    - Daniel Hokka Zakrissoni (@dhozac)
153	    - Ahti Kitsik (@ahtik)
154	    - Jose Angel Munoz (@imjoseangel)
155	'''
156

   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html

157	EXAMPLES = r'''
158	# NOTE: Before 2.3, option 'dest', 'destfile' or 'name' was used instead of 'path'
159	- name: Ensure SELinux is set to enforcing mode
160	  ansible.builtin.lineinfile:
161	    path: /etc/selinux/config
162	    regexp: '^SELINUX='
163	    line: SELINUX=enforcing
164	
165	- name: Make sure group wheel is not in the sudoers configuration
166	  ansible.builtin.lineinfile:
167	    path: /etc/sudoers
168	    state: absent
169	    regexp: '^%wheel'
170	
171	- name: Replace a localhost entry with our own
172	  ansible.builtin.lineinfile:
173	    path: /etc/hosts
174	    regexp: '^127\.0\.0\.1'
175	    line: 127.0.0.1 localhost
176	    owner: root
177	    group: root
178	    mode: '0644'
179	
180	- name: Replace a localhost entry searching for a literal string to avoid escaping
181	  ansible.builtin.lineinfile:
182	    path: /etc/hosts
183	    search_string: '127.0.0.1'
184	    line: 127.0.0.1 localhost
185	    owner: root
186	    group: root
187	    mode: '0644'
188	
189	- name: Ensure the default Apache port is 8080
190	  ansible.builtin.lineinfile:
191	    path: /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf
192	    regexp: '^Listen '
193	    insertafter: '^#Listen '
194	    line: Listen 8080
195	
196	- name: Ensure php extension matches new pattern
197	  ansible.builtin.lineinfile:
198	    path: /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf
199	    search_string: '<FilesMatch ".php[45]?$">'
200	    insertafter: '^\t<Location \/>\n'
201	    line: '        <FilesMatch ".php[34]?$">'
202	
203	- name: Ensure we have our own comment added to /etc/services
204	  ansible.builtin.lineinfile:
205	    path: /etc/services
206	    regexp: '^# port for http'
207	    insertbefore: '^www.*80/tcp'
208	    line: '# port for http by default'
209	
210	- name: Add a line to a file if the file does not exist, without passing regexp
211	  ansible.builtin.lineinfile:
212	    path: /tmp/testfile
213	    line: 192.168.1.99 foo.lab.net foo
214	    create: yes
215	
216	# NOTE: Yaml requires escaping backslashes in double quotes but not in single quotes
217	- name: Ensure the JBoss memory settings are exactly as needed
218	  ansible.builtin.lineinfile:
219	    path: /opt/jboss-as/bin/standalone.conf
220	    regexp: '^(.*)Xms(\d+)m(.*)$'
221	    line: '\1Xms${xms}m\3'
222	    backrefs: yes
223	
224	# NOTE: Fully quoted because of the ': ' on the line. See the Gotchas in the YAML docs.
225	- name: Validate the sudoers file before saving
226	  ansible.builtin.lineinfile:
227	    path: /etc/sudoers
228	    state: present
229	    regexp: '^%ADMIN ALL='
230	    line: '%ADMIN ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: ALL'
231	    validate: /usr/sbin/visudo -cf %s
232	
233	# See https://docs.python.org/3/library/re.html for further details on syntax
234	- name: Use backrefs with alternative group syntax to avoid conflicts with variable values
235	  ansible.builtin.lineinfile:
236	    path: /tmp/config
237	    regexp: ^(host=).*
238	    line: \g<1>{{ hostname }}
239	    backrefs: yes
240	'''

9	DOCUMENTATION = '''
10	---
11	module: pip
12	short_description: Manages Python library dependencies
13	description:
14	     - "Manage Python library dependencies. To use this module, one of the following keys is required: O(name)
15	       or O(requirements)."
16	version_added: "0.7"
17	options:
18	  name:
19	    description:
20	      - The name of a Python library to install or the url(bzr+,hg+,git+,svn+) of the remote package.
21	      - This can be a list (since 2.2) and contain version specifiers (since 2.7).
22	    type: list
23	    elements: str
24	  version:
25	    description:
26	      - The version number to install of the Python library specified in the O(name) parameter.
27	    type: str
28	  requirements:
29	    description:
30	      - The path to a pip requirements file, which should be local to the remote system.
31	        File can be specified as a relative path if using the O(chdir) option.
32	    type: str
33	  virtualenv:
34	    description:
35	      - An optional path to a I(virtualenv) directory to install into.
36	        It cannot be specified together with the O(executable) parameter
37	        (added in 2.1).
38	        If the virtualenv does not exist, it will be created before installing
39	        packages. The optional O(virtualenv_site_packages), O(virtualenv_command),
40	        and O(virtualenv_python) options affect the creation of the virtualenv.
41	    type: path
42	  virtualenv_site_packages:
43	    description:
44	      - Whether the virtual environment will inherit packages from the
45	        global C(site-packages) directory. Note that if this setting is
46	        changed on an already existing virtual environment it will not
47	        have any effect, the environment must be deleted and newly
48	        created.
49	    type: bool
50	    default: "no"
51	    version_added: "1.0"
52	  virtualenv_command:
53	    description:
54	      - The command or a pathname to the command to create the virtual
55	        environment with. For example V(pyvenv), V(virtualenv),
56	        V(virtualenv2), V(~/bin/virtualenv), V(/usr/local/bin/virtualenv).
57	    type: path
58	    default: virtualenv
59	    version_added: "1.1"
60	  virtualenv_python:
61	    description:
62	      - The Python executable used for creating the virtual environment.
63	        For example V(python3.12), V(python2.7). When not specified, the
64	        Python version used to run the ansible module is used. This parameter
65	        should not be used when O(virtualenv_command) is using V(pyvenv) or
66	        the C(-m venv) module.
67	    type: str
68	    version_added: "2.0"
69	  state:
70	    description:
71	      - The state of module.
72	      - The V(forcereinstall) option is only available in Ansible 2.1 and above.
73	    type: str
74	    choices: [ absent, forcereinstall, latest, present ]
75	    default: present
76	  extra_args:
77	    description:
78	      - Extra arguments passed to C(pip).
79	    type: str
80	    version_added: "1.0"
81	  editable:
82	    description:
83	      - Pass the editable flag.
84	    type: bool
85	    default: 'no'
86	    version_added: "2.0"
87	  chdir:
88	    description:
89	      - cd into this directory before running the command.
90	    type: path
91	    version_added: "1.3"
92	  executable:
93	    description:
94	      - The explicit executable or pathname for the C(pip) executable,
95	        if different from the Ansible Python interpreter. For
96	        example V(pip3.3), if there are both Python 2.7 and 3.3 installations
97	        in the system and you want to run pip for the Python 3.3 installation.
98	      - Mutually exclusive with O(virtualenv) (added in 2.1).
99	      - Does not affect the Ansible Python interpreter.
100	      - The C(setuptools) package must be installed for both the Ansible Python interpreter
101	        and for the version of Python specified by this option.
102	    type: path
103	    version_added: "1.3"
104	  umask:
105	    description:
106	      - The system umask to apply before installing the pip package. This is
107	        useful, for example, when installing on systems that have a very
108	        restrictive umask by default (e.g., C(0077)) and you want to C(pip install)
109	        packages which are to be used by all users. Note that this requires you
110	        to specify desired umask mode as an octal string, (e.g., C(0022)).
111	    type: str
112	    version_added: "2.1"
113	  break_system_packages:
114	    description:
115	      - Allow C(pip) to modify an externally-managed Python installation as defined by PEP 668.
116	      - This is typically required when installing packages outside a virtual environment on modern systems.
117	    type: bool
118	    default: false
119	    version_added: "2.17"
120	extends_documentation_fragment:
121	  -  action_common_attributes
122	attributes:
123	    check_mode:
124	        support: full
125	    diff_mode:
126	        support: none
127	    platform:
128	        platforms: posix
129	notes:
130	   - Python installations marked externally-managed (as defined by PEP668) cannot be updated by pip versions >= 23.0.1 without the use of
131	     a virtual environment or setting the O(break_system_packages) option.
132	   - The virtualenv (U(http://www.virtualenv.org/)) must be
133	     installed on the remote host if the virtualenv parameter is specified and
134	     the virtualenv needs to be created.
135	   - Although it executes using the Ansible Python interpreter, the pip module shells out to
136	     run the actual pip command, so it can use any pip version you specify with O(executable).
137	     By default, it uses the pip version for the Ansible Python interpreter. For example, pip3 on python 3, and pip2 or pip on python 2.
138	   - The interpreter used by Ansible
139	     (see R(ansible_python_interpreter, ansible_python_interpreter))
140	     requires the setuptools package, regardless of the version of pip set with
141	     the O(executable) option.
142	requirements:
143	- pip
144	- virtualenv
145	- setuptools or packaging
146	author:
147	- Matt Wright (@mattupstate)
148	'''

10	DOCUMENTATION = r'''
11	---
12	module: replace
13	author: Evan Kaufman (@EvanK)
14	extends_documentation_fragment:
15	    - action_common_attributes
16	    - action_common_attributes.files
17	    - files
18	    - validate
19	attributes:
20	    check_mode:
21	        support: full
22	    diff_mode:
23	        support: full
24	    platform:
25	        platforms: posix
26	    safe_file_operations:
27	        support: full
28	    vault:
29	        support: none
30	short_description: Replace all instances of a particular string in a
31	                   file using a back-referenced regular expression
32	description:
33	  - This module will replace all instances of a pattern within a file.
34	  - It is up to the user to maintain idempotence by ensuring that the
35	    same pattern would never match any replacements made.
36	version_added: "1.6"
37	options:
38	  path:
39	    description:
40	      - The file to modify.
41	      - Before Ansible 2.3 this option was only usable as O(dest), O(destfile) and O(name).
42	    type: path
43	    required: true
44	    aliases: [ dest, destfile, name ]
45	  regexp:
46	    description:
47	      - The regular expression to look for in the contents of the file.
48	      - Uses Python regular expressions; see
49	        U(https://docs.python.org/3/library/re.html).
50	      - Uses MULTILINE mode, which means V(^) and V($) match the beginning
51	        and end of the file, as well as the beginning and end respectively
52	        of I(each line) of the file.
53	      - Does not use DOTALL, which means the V(.) special character matches
54	        any character I(except newlines). A common mistake is to assume that
55	        a negated character set like V([^#]) will also not match newlines.
56	      - In order to exclude newlines, they must be added to the set like V([^#\\n]).
57	      - Note that, as of Ansible 2.0, short form tasks should have any escape
58	        sequences backslash-escaped in order to prevent them being parsed
59	        as string literal escapes. See the examples.
60	    type: str
61	    required: true
62	  replace:
63	    description:
64	      - The string to replace regexp matches.
65	      - May contain backreferences that will get expanded with the regexp capture groups if the regexp matches.
66	      - If not set, matches are removed entirely.
67	      - Backreferences can be used ambiguously like V(\\1), or explicitly like V(\\g<1>).
68	    type: str
69	    default: ''
70	  after:
71	    description:
72	      - If specified, only content after this match will be replaced/removed.
73	      - Can be used in combination with O(before).
74	      - Uses Python regular expressions; see
75	        U(https://docs.python.org/3/library/re.html).
76	      - Uses DOTALL, which means the V(.) special character I(can match newlines).
77	      - Does not use MULTILINE, so V(^) and V($) will only match the beginning and end of the file.
78	    type: str
79	    version_added: "2.4"
80	  before:
81	    description:
82	      - If specified, only content before this match will be replaced/removed.
83	      - Can be used in combination with O(after).
84	      - Uses Python regular expressions; see
85	        U(https://docs.python.org/3/library/re.html).
86	      - Uses DOTALL, which means the V(.) special character I(can match newlines).
87	      - Does not use MULTILINE, so V(^) and V($) will only match the beginning and end of the file.
88	    type: str
89	    version_added: "2.4"
90	  backup:
91	    description:
92	      - Create a backup file including the timestamp information so you can
93	        get the original file back if you somehow clobbered it incorrectly.
94	    type: bool
95	    default: no
96	  encoding:
97	    description:
98	      - The character encoding for reading and writing the file.
99	    type: str
100	    default: utf-8
101	    version_added: "2.4"
102	notes:
103	  - As of Ansible 2.3, the O(dest) option has been changed to O(path) as default, but O(dest) still works as well.
104	  - As of Ansible 2.7.10, the combined use of O(before) and O(after) works properly. If you were relying on the
105	    previous incorrect behavior, you may be need to adjust your tasks.
106	    See U(https://github.com/ansible/ansible/issues/31354) for details.
107	  - Option O(ignore:follow) has been removed in Ansible 2.5, because this module modifies the contents of the file
108	    so O(ignore:follow=no) does not make sense.
109	'''

111	EXAMPLES = r'''
112	- name: Replace old hostname with new hostname (requires Ansible >= 2.4)
113	  ansible.builtin.replace:
114	    path: /etc/hosts
115	    regexp: '(\s+)old\.host\.name(\s+.*)?$'
116	    replace: '\1new.host.name\2'
117	
118	- name: Replace after the expression till the end of the file (requires Ansible >= 2.4)
119	  ansible.builtin.replace:
120	    path: /etc/apache2/sites-available/default.conf
121	    after: 'NameVirtualHost [*]'
122	    regexp: '^(.+)$'
123	    replace: '# \1'
124	
125	- name: Replace before the expression from the beginning of the file (requires Ansible >= 2.4)
126	  ansible.builtin.replace:
127	    path: /etc/apache2/sites-available/default.conf
128	    before: '# live site config'
129	    regexp: '^(.+)$'
130	    replace: '# \1'
131	
132	# Prior to Ansible 2.7.10, using before and after in combination did the opposite of what was intended.
133	# see https://github.com/ansible/ansible/issues/31354 for details.
134	# Note (?m) which turns on MULTILINE mode so ^ matches any line's beginning
135	- name: Replace between the expressions (requires Ansible >= 2.4)
136	  ansible.builtin.replace:
137	    path: /etc/hosts
138	    after: '(?m)^<VirtualHost [*]>'
139	    before: '</VirtualHost>'
140	    regexp: '^(.+)$'
141	    replace: '# \1'
142	
143	- name: Supports common file attributes
144	  ansible.builtin.replace:
145	    path: /home/jdoe/.ssh/known_hosts
146	    regexp: '^old\.host\.name[^\n]*\n'
147	    owner: jdoe
148	    group: jdoe
149	    mode: '0644'
150	
151	- name: Supports a validate command
152	  ansible.builtin.replace:
153	    path: /etc/apache/ports
154	    regexp: '^(NameVirtualHost|Listen)\s+80\s*$'
155	    replace: '\1 127.0.0.1:8080'
156	    validate: '/usr/sbin/apache2ctl -f %s -t'
157	
158	- name: Short form task (in ansible 2+) necessitates backslash-escaped sequences
159	  ansible.builtin.replace: path=/etc/hosts regexp='\\b(localhost)(\\d*)\\b' replace='\\1\\2.localdomain\\2 \\1\\2'
160	
161	- name: Long form task does not
162	  ansible.builtin.replace:
163	    path: /etc/hosts
164	    regexp: '\b(localhost)(\d*)\b'
165	    replace: '\1\2.localdomain\2 \1\2'
166	
167	- name: Explicitly specifying positional matched groups in replacement
168	  ansible.builtin.replace:
169	    path: /etc/ssh/sshd_config
170	    regexp: '^(ListenAddress[ ]+)[^\n]+$'
171	    replace: '\g<1>0.0.0.0'
172	
173	- name: Explicitly specifying named matched groups
174	  ansible.builtin.replace:
175	    path: /etc/ssh/sshd_config
176	    regexp: '^(?P<dctv>ListenAddress[ ]+)(?P<host>[^\n]+)$'
177	    replace: '#\g<dctv>\g<host>\n\g<dctv>0.0.0.0'
178	'''

   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
8	
9	DOCUMENTATION = r'''
10	---
11	module: set_fact
12	short_description: Set host variable(s) and fact(s).
13	version_added: "1.2"
14	description:
15	    - This action allows setting variables associated to the current host.
16	    - These variables will be available to subsequent plays during an ansible-playbook run via the host they were set on.
17	    - Set O(cacheable) to V(true) to save variables across executions using a fact cache.
18	      Variables will keep the set_fact precedence for the current run, but will used 'cached fact' precedence for subsequent ones.
19	    - Per the standard Ansible variable precedence rules, other types of variables have a higher priority, so this value may be overridden.
20	options:
21	  key_value:
22	    description:
23	      - "The M(ansible.builtin.set_fact) module takes C(key=value) pairs or C(key: value) (YAML notation) as variables to set in the playbook scope.
24	        The 'key' is the resulting variable name and the value is, of course, the value of said variable."
25	      - You can create multiple variables at once, by supplying multiple pairs, but do NOT mix notations.
26	    required: true
27	  cacheable:
28	    description:
29	      - This boolean converts the variable into an actual 'fact' which will also be added to the fact cache.
30	        It does not enable fact caching across runs, it just means it will work with it if already enabled.
31	      - Normally this module creates 'host level variables' and has much higher precedence, this option changes the nature and precedence
32	        (by 7 steps) of the variable created.
33	        U(https://docs.ansible.com/ansible/latest/user_guide/playbooks_variables.html#variable-precedence-where-should-i-put-a-variable)
34	      - "This actually creates 2 copies of the variable, a normal 'set_fact' host variable with high precedence and
35	        a lower 'ansible_fact' one that is available for persistence via the facts cache plugin.
36	        This creates a possibly confusing interaction with C(meta: clear_facts) as it will remove the 'ansible_fact' but not the host variable."
37	    type: bool
38	    default: no
39	    version_added: "2.4"
40	extends_documentation_fragment:
41	    - action_common_attributes
42	    - action_common_attributes.conn
43	    - action_common_attributes.flow
44	    - action_core
45	attributes:
46	    action:
47	        details: While the action plugin does do some of the work it relies on the core engine to actually create the variables, that part cannot be overridden
48	        support: partial
49	    bypass_host_loop:
50	        support: none
51	    bypass_task_loop:
52	        support: none
53	    check_mode:
54	        support: full
55	    core:
56	        details: While parts of this action are implemented in core, other parts are still available as normal plugins and can be partially overridden
57	        support: partial
58	    delegation:
59	        details:
60	            - while variable assignment can be delegated to a different host the execution context is always the current inventory_hostname
61	            - connection variables, if set at all, would reflect the host it would target, even if we are not connecting at all in this case
62	        support: partial
63	    diff_mode:
64	        support: none
65	notes:
66	    - Because of the nature of tasks, set_fact will produce 'static' values for a variable.
67	      Unlike normal 'lazy' variables, the value gets evaluated and templated on assignment.
68	    - Some boolean values (yes, no, true, false) will always be converted to boolean type,
69	      unless C(DEFAULT_JINJA2_NATIVE) is enabled.  This is done so the C(var=value) booleans,
70	      otherwise it would only be able to create strings, but it also prevents using those values to create YAML strings.
71	      Using the setting will restrict k=v to strings, but will allow you to specify string or boolean in YAML.
72	    - "To create lists/arrays or dictionary/hashes use YAML notation C(var: [val1, val2])."
73	    - Since 'cacheable' is now a module param, 'cacheable' is no longer a valid fact name.
74	seealso:
75	- module: ansible.builtin.include_vars
76	- ref: ansible_variable_precedence
77	  description: More information related to variable precedence and which type of variable wins over others.
78	author:
79	- Dag Wieers (@dagwieers)
80	'''
81

27	              V(ssh_host_key_rsa_public), V(ssh_host_pub_keys), V(ssh_pub_keys), V(system), V(system_capabilities),
28	              V(system_capabilities_enforced), V(systemd), V(user), V(user_dir), V(user_gecos), V(user_gid), V(user_id),
29	              V(user_shell), V(user_uid), V(virtual), V(virtualization_role), V(virtualization_type).
30	              Can specify a list of values to specify a larger subset.
31	              Values can also be used with an initial C(!) to specify that
32	              that specific subset should not be collected.  For instance:
33	              V(!hardware,!network,!virtual,!ohai,!facter). If V(!all) is specified
34	              then only the min subset is collected. To avoid collecting even the
35	              min subset, specify V(!all,!min). To collect only specific facts,
36	              use V(!all,!min), and specify the particular fact subsets.
37	              Use the filter parameter if you do not want to display some collected
38	              facts."
39	        type: list
40	        elements: str
41	        default: "all"
42	    gather_timeout:
43	        version_added: "2.2"
44	        description:
45	            - Set the default timeout in seconds for individual fact gathering.
46	        type: int
47	        default: 10
48	    filter:
49	        version_added: "1.1"
50	        description:
51	            - If supplied, only return facts that match one of the shell-style
52	              (fnmatch) pattern. An empty list basically means 'no filter'.
53	              As of Ansible 2.11, the type has changed from string to list
54	              and the default has became an empty list. A simple string is
55	              still accepted and works as a single pattern. The behaviour
56	              prior to Ansible 2.11 remains.
57	        type: list
58	        elements: str
59	        default: []
60	    fact_path:
61	        version_added: "1.3"
62	        description:
63	            - Path used for local ansible facts (C(*.fact)) - files in this dir
64	              will be run (if executable) and their results be added to C(ansible_local) facts.
65	              If a file is not executable it is read instead.
66	              File/results format can be JSON or INI-format. The default O(fact_path) can be
67	              specified in C(ansible.cfg) for when setup is automatically called as part of
68	              C(gather_facts).
69	              NOTE - For windows clients, the results will be added to a variable named after the
70	              local file (without extension suffix), rather than C(ansible_local).
71	            - Since Ansible 2.1, Windows hosts can use O(fact_path). Make sure that this path
72	              exists on the target host. Files in this path MUST be PowerShell scripts C(.ps1)
73	              which outputs an object. This object will be formatted by Ansible as json so the
74	              script should be outputting a raw hashtable, array, or other primitive object.
75	        type: path
76	        default: /etc/ansible/facts.d
77	description:
78	    - This module is automatically called by playbooks to gather useful
79	      variables about remote hosts that can be used in playbooks. It can also be
80	      executed directly by C(/usr/bin/ansible) to check what variables are
81	      available to a host. Ansible provides many I(facts) about the system,
82	      automatically.
83	    - This module is also supported for Windows targets.
84	extends_documentation_fragment:
85	  -  action_common_attributes
86	  -  action_common_attributes.facts
87	attributes:
88	    check_mode:
89	        support: full
90	    diff_mode:
91	        support: none
92	    facts:
93	        support: full
94	    platform:
95	        platforms: posix, windows
96	notes:
97	    - More ansible facts will be added with successive releases. If I(facter) or
98	      I(ohai) are installed, variables from these programs will also be snapshotted
99	      into the JSON file for usage in templating. These variables are prefixed
100	      with C(facter_) and C(ohai_) so it's easy to tell their source. All variables are
101	      bubbled up to the caller. Using the ansible facts and choosing to not
102	      install I(facter) and I(ohai) means you can avoid Ruby-dependencies on your
103	      remote systems. (See also M(community.general.facter) and M(community.general.ohai).)
104	    - The filter option filters only the first level subkey below ansible_facts.
105	    - If the target host is Windows, you will not currently have the ability to use
106	      O(filter) as this is provided by a simpler implementation of the module.
107	    - This module should be run with elevated privileges on BSD systems to gather facts like ansible_product_version.
108	    - For more information about delegated facts,
109	      please check U(https://docs.ansible.com/ansible/latest/user_guide/playbooks_delegation.html#delegating-facts).
110	author:
111	    - "Ansible Core Team"
112	    - "Michael DeHaan"

13	description:
14	  - Interacts with HTTP and HTTPS web services and supports Digest, Basic and WSSE
15	    HTTP authentication mechanisms.

21	      - SSL/TLS Ciphers to use for the request.
22	      - 'When a list is provided, all ciphers are joined in order with V(:)'
23	      - See the L(OpenSSL Cipher List Format,https://www.openssl.org/docs/manmaster/man1/openssl-ciphers.html#CIPHER-LIST-FORMAT)
24	        for more details.
25	      - The available ciphers is dependent on the Python and OpenSSL/LibreSSL versions.
26	    type: list
27	    elements: str
28	    version_added: '2.14'
29	  decompress:
30	    description:
31	      - Whether to attempt to decompress gzip content-encoded responses.
32	    type: bool
33	    default: true
34	    version_added: '2.14'
35	  url:
36	    description:
37	      - HTTP or HTTPS URL in the form (http|https)://host.domain[:port]/path.
38	    type: str
39	    required: true
40	  dest:
41	    description:
42	      - A path of where to download the file to (if desired). If O(dest) is a
43	        directory, the basename of the file on the remote server will be used.
44	    type: path
45	  url_username:
46	    description:
47	      - A username for the module to use for Digest, Basic or WSSE authentication.
48	    type: str
49	    aliases: [ user ]
50	  url_password:
51	    description:
52	      - A password for the module to use for Digest, Basic or WSSE authentication.
53	    type: str
54	    aliases: [ password ]
55	  body:
56	    description:
57	      - The body of the http request/response to the web service. If O(body_format) is set
58	        to V(json) it will take an already formatted JSON string or convert a data structure
59	        into JSON.
60	      - If O(body_format) is set to V(form-urlencoded) it will convert a dictionary
61	        or list of tuples into an C(application/x-www-form-urlencoded) string. (Added in v2.7)
62	      - If O(body_format) is set to V(form-multipart) it will convert a dictionary
63	        into C(multipart/form-multipart) body. (Added in v2.10)
64	    type: raw
65	  body_format:
66	    description:
67	      - The serialization format of the body. When set to V(json), V(form-multipart), or V(form-urlencoded), encodes
68	        the body argument, if needed, and automatically sets the C(Content-Type) header accordingly.
69	      - As of v2.3 it is possible to override the C(Content-Type) header, when
70	        set to V(json) or V(form-urlencoded) via the O(headers) option.
71	      - The C(Content-Type) header cannot be overridden when using V(form-multipart).
72	      - V(form-urlencoded) was added in v2.7.
73	      - V(form-multipart) was added in v2.10.
74	    type: str
75	    choices: [ form-urlencoded, json, raw, form-multipart ]
76	    default: raw
77	    version_added: "2.0"
78	  method:
79	    description:
80	      - The HTTP method of the request or response.
81	      - In more recent versions we do not restrict the method at the module level anymore
82	        but it still must be a valid method accepted by the service handling the request.
83	    type: str
84	    default: GET
85	  return_content:
86	    description:
87	      - Whether or not to return the body of the response as a "content" key in
88	        the dictionary result no matter it succeeded or failed.
89	      - Independently of this option, if the reported C(Content-Type) is C(application/json), then the JSON is
90	        always loaded into a key called RV(ignore:json) in the dictionary results.
91	    type: bool
92	    default: no
93	  force_basic_auth:
94	    description:
95	      - Force the sending of the Basic authentication header upon initial request.
96	      - When this setting is V(false), this module will first try an unauthenticated request, and when the server replies
97	        with an C(HTTP 401) error, it will submit the Basic authentication header.
98	      - When this setting is V(true), this module will immediately send a Basic authentication header on the first
99	        request.
100	      - "Use this setting in any of the following scenarios:"
101	      - You know the webservice endpoint always requires HTTP Basic authentication, and you want to speed up your
102	        requests by eliminating the first roundtrip.
103	      - The web service does not properly send an HTTP 401 error to your client, so Ansible's HTTP library will not
104	        properly respond with HTTP credentials, and logins will fail.
105	      - The webservice bans or rate-limits clients that cause any HTTP 401 errors.
106	    type: bool
107	    default: no
108	  follow_redirects:
109	    description:
110	      - Whether or not the URI module should follow redirects.
111	    type: str
112	    default: safe
113	    choices:
114	      all: Will follow all redirects.
115	      none: Will not follow any redirects.
116	      safe: Only redirects doing GET or HEAD requests will be followed.
117	      urllib2: Defer to urllib2 behavior (As of writing this follows HTTP redirects).
118	      'no': (DEPRECATED, removed in 2.22) alias of V(none).
119	      'yes': (DEPRECATED, removed in 2.22) alias of V(all).
120	  creates:
121	    description:
122	      - A filename, when it already exists, this step will not be run.
123	    type: path
124	  removes:
125	    description:
126	      - A filename, when it does not exist, this step will not be run.
127	    type: path
128	  status_code:
129	    description:
130	      - A list of valid, numeric, HTTP status codes that signifies success of the request.
131	    type: list
132	    elements: int
133	    default: [ 200 ]
134	  timeout:
135	    description:
136	      - The socket level timeout in seconds
137	    type: int
138	    default: 30
139	  headers:
140	    description:
141	        - Add custom HTTP headers to a request in the format of a YAML hash. As
142	          of Ansible 2.3 supplying C(Content-Type) here will override the header
143	          generated by supplying V(json) or V(form-urlencoded) for O(body_format).
144	    type: dict
145	    default: {}
146	    version_added: '2.1'
147	  validate_certs:
148	    description:
149	      - If V(false), SSL certificates will not be validated.
150	      - This should only set to V(false) used on personally controlled sites using self-signed certificates.
151	      - Prior to 1.9.2 the code defaulted to V(false).
152	    type: bool
153	    default: true
154	    version_added: '1.9.2'
155	  client_cert:
156	    description:
157	      - PEM formatted certificate chain file to be used for SSL client authentication.
158	      - This file can also include the key as well, and if the key is included, O(client_key) is not required.
159	    type: path
160	    version_added: '2.4'
161	  client_key:
162	    description:
163	      - PEM formatted file that contains your private key to be used for SSL client authentication.
164	      - If O(client_cert) contains both the certificate and key, this option is not required.
165	    type: path
166	    version_added: '2.4'
167	  ca_path:
168	    description:
169	      - PEM formatted file that contains a CA certificate to be used for validation.
170	    type: path
171	    version_added: '2.11'
172	  src:
173	    description:
174	      - Path to file to be submitted to the remote server.
175	      - Cannot be used with O(body).
176	      - Should be used with O(force_basic_auth) to ensure success when the remote end sends a 401.
177	    type: path
178	    version_added: '2.7'
179	  remote_src:
180	    description:
181	      - If V(false), the module will search for the O(src) on the controller node.
182	      - If V(true), the module will search for the O(src) on the managed (remote) node.
183	    type: bool
184	    default: no
185	    version_added: '2.7'
186	  force:
187	    description:
188	      - If V(true) do not get a cached copy.
189	    type: bool
190	    default: no
191	  use_proxy:
192	    description:
193	      - If V(false), it will not use a proxy, even if one is defined in an environment variable on the target hosts.
194	    type: bool
195	    default: true
196	  unix_socket:
197	    description:
198	    - Path to Unix domain socket to use for connection.
199	    type: path
200	    version_added: '2.8'
201	  http_agent:
202	    description:
203	      - Header to identify as, generally appears in web server logs.
204	    type: str
205	    default: ansible-httpget
206	  unredirected_headers:
207	    description:
208	      - A list of header names that will not be sent on subsequent redirected requests. This list is case
209	        insensitive. By default all headers will be redirected. In some cases it may be beneficial to list
210	        headers such as C(Authorization) here to avoid potential credential exposure.
211	    default: []
212	    type: list
213	    elements: str
214	    version_added: '2.12'
215	  use_gssapi:
216	    description:
217	      - Use GSSAPI to perform the authentication, typically this is for Kerberos or Kerberos through Negotiate
218	        authentication.
219	      - Requires the Python library L(gssapi,https://github.com/pythongssapi/python-gssapi) to be installed.
220	      - Credentials for GSSAPI can be specified with O(url_username)/O(url_password) or with the GSSAPI env var
221	        C(KRB5CCNAME) that specified a custom Kerberos credential cache.
222	      - NTLM authentication is B(not) supported even if the GSSAPI mech for NTLM has been installed.
223	    type: bool
224	    default: no
225	    version_added: '2.11'
226	  use_netrc:
227	    description:
228	      - Determining whether to use credentials from C(~/.netrc) file.
229	      - By default C(.netrc) is used with Basic authentication headers.
230	      - When V(false), C(.netrc) credentials are ignored.
231	    type: bool
232	    default: true
233	    version_added: '2.14'
234	extends_documentation_fragment:
235	  - action_common_attributes
236	  - files
237	attributes:
238	    check_mode:
239	        support: none
240	    diff_mode:
241	        support: none
242	    platform:
243	        platforms: posix
244	notes:
245	  - The dependency on httplib2 was removed in Ansible 2.1.
246	  - The module returns all the HTTP headers in lower-case.
247	  - For Windows targets, use the M(ansible.windows.win_uri) module instead.
248	seealso:
249	- module: ansible.builtin.get_url
250	- module: ansible.windows.win_uri
251	author:
252	- Romeo Theriault (@romeotheriault)
253	'''
