9	DOCUMENTATION = r'''
10	module: user
11	version_added: "0.2"
12	short_description: Manage user accounts
13	description:
14	    - Manage user accounts and user attributes.
15	    - For Windows targets, use the M(ansible.windows.win_user) module instead.
16	options:
17	    name:
18	        description:
19	            - Name of the user to create, remove or modify.
20	        type: str
21	        required: true
22	        aliases: [ user ]
23	    uid:
24	        description:
25	            - Optionally sets the I(UID) of the user.
26	        type: int
27	    comment:
28	        description:
29	            - Optionally sets the description (aka I(GECOS)) of user account.
30	            - On macOS, this defaults to the O(name) option.
31	        type: str
32	    hidden:
33	        description:
34	            - macOS only, optionally hide the user from the login window and system preferences.
35	            - The default will be V(true) if the O(system) option is used.
36	        type: bool
37	        version_added: "2.6"
38	    non_unique:
39	        description:
40	            - Optionally when used with the C(-u) option, this option allows to change the user ID to a non-unique value.
41	        type: bool
42	        default: no
43	        version_added: "1.1"
44	    seuser:
45	        description:
46	            - Optionally sets the C(seuser) type C(user_u) on SELinux enabled systems.
47	        type: str
48	        version_added: "2.1"
49	    group:
50	        description:
51	            - Optionally sets the user's primary group (takes a group name).
52	            - On macOS, this defaults to V(staff).
53	        type: str
54	    groups:
55	        description:
56	            - A list of supplementary groups which the user is also a member of.
57	            - By default, the user is removed from all other groups. Configure O(append) to modify this.
58	            - When set to an empty string V(''),
59	              the user is removed from all groups except the primary group.
60	            - Before Ansible 2.3, the only input format allowed was a comma separated string.
61	        type: list
62	        elements: str
63	    append:
64	        description:
65	            - If V(true), add the user to the groups specified in O(groups).
66	            - If V(false), user will only be added to the groups specified in O(groups),
67	              removing them from all other groups.
68	        type: bool
69	        default: no
70	    shell:
71	        description:
72	            - Optionally set the user's shell.
73	            - On macOS, before Ansible 2.5, the default shell for non-system users was V(/usr/bin/false).
74	              Since Ansible 2.5, the default shell for non-system users on macOS is V(/bin/bash).
75	            - On other operating systems, the default shell is determined by the underlying tool
76	              invoked by this module. See Notes for a per platform list of invoked tools.
77	            - From Ansible 2.18, the type is changed to I(path) from I(str).
78	        type: path
79	    home:
80	        description:
81	            - Optionally set the user's home directory.
82	        type: path
83	    skeleton:
84	        description:
85	            - Optionally set a home skeleton directory.
86	            - Requires O(create_home) option!
87	        type: str
88	        version_added: "2.0"
89	    password:
90	        description:
91	            - If provided, set the user's password to the provided encrypted hash (Linux) or plain text password (macOS).
92	            - B(Linux/Unix/POSIX:) Enter the hashed password as the value.
93	            - See L(FAQ entry,https://docs.ansible.com/ansible/latest/reference_appendices/faq.html#how-do-i-generate-encrypted-passwords-for-the-user-module)
94	              for details on various ways to generate the hash of a password.
95	            - To create an account with a locked/disabled password on Linux systems, set this to V('!') or V('*').
96	            - To create an account with a locked/disabled password on OpenBSD, set this to V('*************').
97	            - B(OS X/macOS:) Enter the cleartext password as the value. Be sure to take relevant security precautions.
98	            - On macOS, the password specified in the C(password) option will always be set, regardless of whether the user account already exists or not.
99	            - When the password is passed as an argument, the M(ansible.builtin.user) module will always return changed to C(true) for macOS systems.
100	              Since macOS no longer provides access to the hashed passwords directly.
101	        type: str
102	    state:
103	        description:
104	            - Whether the account should exist or not, taking action if the state is different from what is stated.
105	            - See this L(FAQ entry,https://docs.ansible.com/ansible/latest/reference_appendices/faq.html#running-on-macos-as-a-target)
106	              for additional requirements when removing users on macOS systems.
107	        type: str
108	        choices: [ absent, present ]
109	        default: present
110	    create_home:
111	        description:
112	            - Unless set to V(false), a home directory will be made for the user
113	              when the account is created or if the home directory does not exist.
114	            - Changed from O(createhome) to O(create_home) in Ansible 2.5.
115	        type: bool
116	        default: yes
117	        aliases: [ createhome ]
118	    move_home:
119	        description:
120	            - "If set to V(true) when used with O(home), attempt to move the user's old home
121	              directory to the specified directory if it isn't there already and the old home exists."
122	        type: bool
123	        default: no
124	    system:
125	        description:
126	            - When creating an account O(state=present), setting this to V(true) makes the user a system account.
127	            - This setting cannot be changed on existing users.
128	        type: bool
129	        default: no
130	    force:
131	        description:
132	            - This only affects O(state=absent), it forces removal of the user and associated directories on supported platforms.
133	            - The behavior is the same as C(userdel --force), check the man page for C(userdel) on your system for details and support.
134	            - When used with O(generate_ssh_key=yes) this forces an existing key to be overwritten.
135	        type: bool
136	        default: no
137	    remove:
138	        description:
139	            - This only affects O(state=absent), it attempts to remove directories associated with the user.
140	            - The behavior is the same as C(userdel --remove), check the man page for details and support.
141	        type: bool
142	        default: no
143	    login_class:
144	        description:
145	            - Optionally sets the user's login class, a feature of most BSD OSs.
146	        type: str
147	    generate_ssh_key:
148	        description:
149	            - Whether to generate a SSH key for the user in question.
150	            - This will B(not) overwrite an existing SSH key unless used with O(force=yes).
151	        type: bool
152	        default: no
153	        version_added: "0.9"
154	    ssh_key_bits:
155	        description:
156	            - Optionally specify number of bits in SSH key to create.
157	            - The default value depends on C(ssh-keygen).
158	        type: int
159	        version_added: "0.9"
160	    ssh_key_type:
161	        description:
162	            - Optionally specify the type of SSH key to generate.
163	            - Available SSH key types will depend on implementation
164	              present on target host.
165	        type: str
166	        default: rsa
167	        version_added: "0.9"
168	    ssh_key_file:
169	        description:
170	            - Optionally specify the SSH key filename.
171	            - If this is a relative filename then it will be relative to the user's home directory.
172	            - This parameter defaults to V(.ssh/id_rsa).
173	        type: path
174	        version_added: "0.9"
175	    ssh_key_comment:
176	        description:
177	            - Optionally define the comment for the SSH key.
178	        type: str
179	        default: ansible-generated on $HOSTNAME
180	        version_added: "0.9"
181	    ssh_key_passphrase:
182	        description:
183	            - Set a passphrase for the SSH key.
184	            - If no passphrase is provided, the SSH key will default to having no passphrase.
185	        type: str
186	        version_added: "0.9"
187	    update_password:
188	        description:
189	            - V(always) will update passwords if they differ.
190	            - V(on_create) will only set the password for newly created users.
191	        type: str
192	        choices: [ always, on_create ]
193	        default: always
194	        version_added: "1.3"
195	    expires:
196	        description:
197	            - An expiry time for the user in epoch, it will be ignored on platforms that do not support this.
198	            - Currently supported on GNU/Linux, FreeBSD, and DragonFlyBSD.
199	            - Since Ansible 2.6 you can remove the expiry time by specifying a negative value.
200	              Currently supported on GNU/Linux and FreeBSD.
201	        type: float
202	        version_added: "1.9"
203	    password_lock:
204	        description:
205	            - Lock the password (C(usermod -L), C(usermod -U), C(pw lock)).
206	            - Implementation differs by platform. This option does not always mean the user cannot login using other methods.
207	            - This option does not disable the user, only lock the password.
208	            - This must be set to V(false) in order to unlock a currently locked password. The absence of this parameter will not unlock a password.
209	            - Currently supported on Linux, FreeBSD, DragonFlyBSD, NetBSD, OpenBSD.
210	        type: bool
211	        version_added: "2.6"
212	    local:
213	        description:
214	            - Forces the use of "local" command alternatives on platforms that implement it.
215	            - This is useful in environments that use centralized authentication when you want to manipulate the local users
216	              (in other words, it uses C(luseradd) instead of C(useradd)).
217	            - This will check C(/etc/passwd) for an existing account before invoking commands. If the local account database
218	              exists somewhere other than C(/etc/passwd), this setting will not work properly.
219	            - This requires that the above commands as well as C(/etc/passwd) must exist on the target host, otherwise it will be a fatal error.
220	        type: bool
221	        default: no
222	        version_added: "2.4"
223	    profile:
224	        description:
225	            - Sets the profile of the user.
226	            - Can set multiple profiles using comma separation.
227	            - To delete all the profiles, use O(profile='').
228	            - Currently supported on Illumos/Solaris. Does nothing when used with other platforms.
229	        type: str
230	        version_added: "2.8"
231	    authorization:
232	        description:
233	            - Sets the authorization of the user.
234	            - Can set multiple authorizations using comma separation.
235	            - To delete all authorizations, use O(authorization='').
236	            - Currently supported on Illumos/Solaris. Does nothing when used with other platforms.
237	        type: str
238	        version_added: "2.8"
239	    role:
240	        description:
241	            - Sets the role of the user.
242	            - Can set multiple roles using comma separation.
243	            - To delete all roles, use O(role='').
244	            - Currently supported on Illumos/Solaris. Does nothing when used with other platforms.
245	        type: str
246	        version_added: "2.8"

250	            - Supported on Linux only.
251	        type: int

254	        description:

256	            - Supported on Linux only.
257	        type: int

261	            - Number of days of warning before password expires.
262	            - Supported on Linux only.
263	        type: int
264	        version_added: "2.16"
265	    umask:
266	        description:
267	            - Sets the umask of the user.
268	            - Currently supported on Linux. Does nothing when used with other platforms.
269	            - Requires O(local) is omitted or V(false).
270	        type: str
271	        version_added: "2.12"
272	    password_expire_account_disable:
273	        description:
274	            - Number of days after a password expires until the account is disabled.
275	            - Currently supported on AIX, Linux, NetBSD, OpenBSD.
276	        type: int
277	        version_added: "2.18"
278	    uid_min:
279	        description:
280	            - Sets the UID_MIN value for user creation.
281	            - Overwrites /etc/login.defs default value.
282	            - Currently supported on Linux. Does nothing when used with other platforms.
283	            - Requires O(local) is omitted or V(False).
284	        type: int
285	        version_added: "2.18"
286	    uid_max:
287	        description:
288	            - Sets the UID_MAX value for user creation.
289	            - Overwrites /etc/login.defs default value.
290	            - Currently supported on Linux. Does nothing when used with other platforms.
291	            - Requires O(local) is omitted or V(False).
292	        type: int
293	        version_added: "2.18"
294	
295	extends_documentation_fragment: action_common_attributes
296	attributes:
297	    check_mode:
298	        support: full
299	    diff_mode:
300	        support: none
301	    platform:
302	        platforms: posix
303	notes:
304	  - There are specific requirements per platform on user management utilities. However
305	    they generally come pre-installed with the system and Ansible will require they
306	    are present at runtime. If they are not, a descriptive error message will be shown.
307	  - On SunOS platforms, the shadow file is backed up automatically since this module edits it directly.
308	    On other platforms, the shadow file is backed up by the underlying tools used by this module.
309	  - On macOS, this module uses C(dscl) to create, modify, and delete accounts. C(dseditgroup) is used to
310	    modify group membership. Accounts are hidden from the login window by modifying
311	    C(/Library/Preferences/com.apple.loginwindow.plist).
312	  - On FreeBSD, this module uses C(pw useradd) and C(chpass) to create, C(pw usermod) and C(chpass) to modify,
313	    C(pw userdel) remove, C(pw lock) to lock, and C(pw unlock) to unlock accounts.
314	  - On all other platforms, this module uses C(useradd) to create, C(usermod) to modify, and
315	    C(userdel) to remove accounts.
316	seealso:
317	- module: ansible.posix.authorized_key
318	- module: ansible.builtin.group
319	- module: ansible.windows.win_user
320	author:
321	- Stephen Fromm (@sfromm)

477	    $ErrorActionPreference = "Stop"
478	    $WarningPreference = "Continue"
479	    $path = $MyInvocation.UnboundArguments[0]
480	    $fd = [System.IO.File]::Create($path)
481	    $algo = [System.Security.Cryptography.SHA1CryptoServiceProvider]::Create()
482	    $bytes = @()
483	
484	    $bindingFlags = [System.Reflection.BindingFlags]'NonPublic, Instance'
485	    Function Get-Property {
486	        <#
487	        .SYNOPSIS
488	        Gets the private/internal property specified of the object passed in.
489	        #>
490	        Param (
491	            [Parameter(Mandatory=$true, ValueFromPipeline=$true)]
492	            [System.Object]
493	            $Object,
494	
495	            [Parameter(Mandatory=$true, Position=1)]
496	            [System.String]
497	            $Name
498	        )
499	
500	        $Object.GetType().GetProperty($Name, $bindingFlags).GetValue($Object, $null)
501	    }
502	
503	    Function Set-Property {
504	        <#
505	        .SYNOPSIS
506	        Sets the private/internal property specified on the object passed in.
507	        #>
508	        Param (
509	            [Parameter(Mandatory=$true, ValueFromPipeline=$true)]
510	            [System.Object]
511	            $Object,
512	
513	            [Parameter(Mandatory=$true, Position=1)]
514	            [System.String]
515	            $Name,
516	
517	            [Parameter(Mandatory=$true, Position=2)]
518	            [AllowNull()]
519	            [System.Object]
520	            $Value
521	        )
522	
523	        $Object.GetType().GetProperty($Name, $bindingFlags).SetValue($Object, $Value, $null)
524	    }
525	
526	    Function Get-Field {
527	        <#
528	        .SYNOPSIS
529	        Gets the private/internal field specified of the object passed in.
530	        #>
531	        Param (
532	            [Parameter(Mandatory=$true, ValueFromPipeline=$true)]
533	            [System.Object]
534	            $Object,
535	
536	            [Parameter(Mandatory=$true, Position=1)]
537	            [System.String]
538	            $Name
539	        )
540	
541	        $Object.GetType().GetField($Name, $bindingFlags).GetValue($Object)
542	    }
543	
544	    # MaximumAllowedMemory is required to be set to so we can send input data that exceeds the limit on a PS
545	    # Runspace. We use reflection to access/set this property as it is not accessible publicly. This is not ideal
546	    # but works on all PowerShell versions I've tested with. We originally used WinRS to send the raw bytes to the
547	    # host but this falls flat if someone is using a custom PS configuration name so this is a workaround. This
548	    # isn't required for smaller files so if it fails we ignore the error and hope it wasn't needed.
549	    # https://github.com/PowerShell/PowerShell/blob/c8e72d1e664b1ee04a14f226adf655cced24e5f0/src/System.Management.Automation/engine/serialization.cs#L325
550	    try {
551	        $Host | Get-Property 'ExternalHost' | `
552	            Get-Field '_transportManager' | `
553	            Get-Property 'Fragmentor' | `
554	            Get-Property 'DeserializationContext' | `
555	            Set-Property 'MaximumAllowedMemory' $null
556	    } catch {}
557	}
558	process {
559	    $bytes = [System.Convert]::FromBase64String($input)
560	    $algo.TransformBlock($bytes, 0, $bytes.Length, $bytes, 0) > $null
561	    $fd.Write($bytes, 0, $bytes.Length)
562	}
563	end {
564	    $fd.Close()
565	
566	    $algo.TransformFinalBlock($bytes, 0, 0) > $null
567	    $hash = [System.BitConverter]::ToString($algo.Hash).Replace('-', '').ToLowerInvariant()
568	    Write-Output -InputObject "{`"sha1`":`"$hash`"}"
569	}
570	'''
571	
572	        # Get the buffer size of each fragment to send, subtract 82 for the fragment, message, and other header info
573	        # fields that PSRP adds. Adjust to size of the base64 encoded bytes length.
574	        buffer_size = int((self.runspace.connection.max_payload_size - 82) / 4 * 3)

>> Issue: [B824:url_found] url_found
   Severity: Medium   Confidence: Medium
   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/ansible_core-2.18.4/ansible_core-2.18.4/lib/ansible/plugins/inventory/ini.py:5
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
4	
5	DOCUMENTATION = '''
6	    name: ini
7	    version_added: "2.4"
8	    short_description: Uses an Ansible INI file as inventory source.
9	    description:
10	        - INI file based inventory, sections are groups or group related with special C(:modifiers).
11	        - Entries in sections C([group_1]) are hosts, members of the group.
12	        - Hosts can have variables defined inline as key/value pairs separated by C(=).
13	        - The C(children) modifier indicates that the section contains groups.
14	        - The C(vars) modifier indicates that the section contains variables assigned to members of the group.
15	        - Anything found outside a section is considered an 'ungrouped' host.
16	        - Values passed in the INI format using the C(key=value) syntax are interpreted differently depending on where they are declared within your inventory.
17	        - When declared inline with the host, INI values are processed by Python's ast.literal_eval function
18	          (U(https://docs.python.org/3/library/ast.html#ast.literal_eval)) and interpreted as Python literal structures
19	         (strings, numbers, tuples, lists, dicts, booleans, None). If you want a number to be treated as a string, you must quote it.
20	          Host lines accept multiple C(key=value) parameters per line.
21	          Therefore they need a way to indicate that a space is part of a value rather than a separator.
22	        - When declared in a C(:vars) section, INI values are interpreted as strings. For example C(var=FALSE) would create a string equal to C(FALSE).
23	          Unlike host lines, C(:vars) sections accept only a single entry per line, so everything after the C(=) must be the value for the entry.
24	        - Do not rely on types set during definition, always make sure you specify type with a filter when needed when consuming the variable.
25	        - See the Examples for proper quoting to prevent changes to variable type.
26	    notes:
27	        - Enabled in configuration by default.
28	        - Consider switching to YAML format for inventory sources to avoid confusion on the actual type of a variable.
29	          The YAML inventory plugin processes variable values consistently and correctly.
30	'''
31

7	
8	DOCUMENTATION = """
9	    name: password
10	    version_added: "1.1"
11	    author:
12	      - Daniel Hokka Zakrisson (!UNKNOWN) <daniel@hozac.com>
13	      - Javier Candeira (!UNKNOWN) <javier@candeira.com>
14	      - Maykel Moya (!UNKNOWN) <mmoya@speedyrails.com>
15	    short_description: retrieve or generate a random password, stored in a file
16	    description:
17	      - Generates a random plaintext password and stores it in a file at a given filepath.
18	      - If the file exists previously, it will retrieve its contents, behaving just like with_file.
19	      - 'Usage of variables like C("{{ inventory_hostname }}") in the filepath can be used to set up random passwords per host,
20	        which simplifies password management in C("host_vars") variables.'
21	      - A special case is using /dev/null as a path. The password lookup will generate a new random password each time,
22	        but will not write it to /dev/null. This can be used when you need a password without storing it on the controller.
23	    options:
24	      _terms:
25	         description:
26	           - path to the file that stores/will store the passwords
27	         required: True
28	      encrypt:
29	        description:
30	           - Which hash scheme to encrypt the returning password, should be one hash scheme from C(passlib.hash);
31	             V(md5_crypt), V(bcrypt), V(sha256_crypt), V(sha512_crypt).
32	           - If not provided, the password will be returned in plain text.
33	           - Note that the password is always stored as plain text, only the returning password is encrypted.
34	           - Encrypt also forces saving the salt value for idempotence.
35	           - Note that before 2.6 this option was incorrectly labeled as a boolean for a long time.
36	      ident:
37	        description:
38	          - Specify version of Bcrypt algorithm to be used while using O(encrypt) as V(bcrypt).
39	          - The parameter is only available for V(bcrypt) - U(https://passlib.readthedocs.io/en/stable/lib/passlib.hash.bcrypt.html#passlib.hash.bcrypt).
40	          - Other hash types will simply ignore this parameter.
41	          - 'Valid values for this parameter are: V(2), V(2a), V(2y), V(2b).'
42	        type: string
43	        version_added: "2.12"
44	      chars:
45	        version_added: "1.4"
46	        description:
47	          - A list of names that compose a custom character set in the generated passwords.
48	          - This parameter defines the possible character sets in the resulting password, not the required character sets.
49	            If you want to require certain character sets for passwords, you can use the P(community.general.random_string#lookup) lookup plugin.
50	          - 'By default generated passwords contain a random mix of upper and lowercase ASCII letters, the numbers 0-9, and punctuation (". , : - _").'
51	          - "They can be either parts of Python's string module attributes or represented literally ( :, -)."
52	          - "Though string modules can vary by Python version, valid values for both major releases include:
53	            'ascii_lowercase', 'ascii_uppercase', 'digits', 'hexdigits', 'octdigits', 'printable', 'punctuation' and 'whitespace'."
54	          - Be aware that Python's 'hexdigits' includes lower and upper case versions of a-f, so it is not a good choice as it doubles
55	            the chances of those values for systems that won't distinguish case, distorting the expected entropy.
56	          - "when using a comma separated string, to enter comma use two commas ',,' somewhere - preferably at the end.
57	             Quotes and double quotes are not supported."
58	        type: list
59	        elements: str
60	        default: ['ascii_letters', 'digits', ".,:-_"]
61	      length:
62	        description: The length of the generated password.
63	        default: 20
64	        type: integer
65	      seed:
66	        version_added: "2.12"
67	        description:
68	          - A seed to initialize the random number generator.
69	          - Identical seeds will yield identical passwords.
70	          - Use this for random-but-idempotent password generation.
71	        type: str
72	    notes:
73	      - A great alternative to the password lookup plugin,
74	        if you don't need to generate random passwords on a per-host basis,
75	        would be to use Vault in playbooks.
76	        Read the documentation there and consider using it first,
77	        it will be more desirable for most applications.
78	      - If the file already exists, no data will be written to it.
79	        If the file has contents, those contents will be read in as the password.
80	        Empty files cause the password to return as an empty string.
81	      - 'As all lookups, this runs on the Ansible host as the user running the playbook, and "become" does not apply,
82	        the target file must be readable by the playbook user, or, if it does not exist,
83	        the playbook user must have sufficient privileges to create it.
84	        (So, for example, attempts to write into areas such as /etc will fail unless the entire playbook is being run as root).'
85	"""

   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
12	
13	DOCUMENTATION = r'''
14	---
15	module: win_acl
16	version_added: "2.0"
17	short_description: Set file/directory/registry permissions for a system user or group
18	description:
19	- Add or remove rights/permissions for a given user or group for the specified
20	  file, folder, registry key or AppPool identifies.
21	options:
22	  path:
23	    description:
24	    - The path to the file or directory.
25	    type: str
26	    required: yes
27	  user:
28	    description:
29	    - User or Group to add specified rights to act on src file/folder or
30	      registry key.
31	    type: str
32	    required: yes
33	  state:
34	    description:
35	    - Specify whether to add C(present) or remove C(absent) the specified access rule.
36	    type: str
37	    choices: [ absent, present ]
38	    default: present
39	  type:
40	    description:
41	    - Specify whether to allow or deny the rights specified.
42	    type: str
43	    required: yes
44	    choices: [ allow, deny ]
45	  rights:
46	    description:
47	    - The rights/permissions that are to be allowed/denied for the specified
48	      user or group for the item at C(path).
49	    - If C(path) is a file or directory, rights can be any right under MSDN
50	      FileSystemRights U(https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.security.accesscontrol.filesystemrights.aspx).
51	    - If C(path) is a registry key, rights can be any right under MSDN
52	      RegistryRights U(https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.security.accesscontrol.registryrights.aspx).
53	    type: str
54	    required: yes
55	  inherit:
56	    description:
57	    - Inherit flags on the ACL rules.
58	    - Can be specified as a comma separated list, e.g. C(ContainerInherit),
59	      C(ObjectInherit).
60	    - For more information on the choices see MSDN InheritanceFlags enumeration
61	      at U(https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.security.accesscontrol.inheritanceflags.aspx).
62	    - Defaults to C(ContainerInherit, ObjectInherit) for Directories.
63	    type: str
64	    choices: [ ContainerInherit, ObjectInherit ]
65	  propagation:
66	    description:
67	    - Propagation flag on the ACL rules.
68	    - For more information on the choices see MSDN PropagationFlags enumeration
69	      at U(https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.security.accesscontrol.propagationflags.aspx).
70	    type: str
71	    choices: [ InheritOnly, None, NoPropagateInherit ]
72	    default: "None"
73	notes:
74	- If adding ACL's for AppPool identities (available since 2.3), the Windows
75	  Feature "Web-Scripting-Tools" must be enabled.
76	seealso:
77	- module: win_acl_inheritance
78	- module: win_file
79	- module: win_owner
80	- module: win_stat
81	author:
82	- Phil Schwartz (@schwartzmx)
83	- Trond Hindenes (@trondhindenes)
84	- Hans-Joachim Kliemeck (@h0nIg)
85	'''
86

>> Issue: [B824:url_found] url_found
   Severity: Medium   Confidence: Medium
   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/ansible_core-2.18.4/ansible_core-2.18.4/test/support/windows-integration/collections/ansible_collections/ansible/windows/plugins/modules/win_shell.py:11
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
10	
11	DOCUMENTATION = r'''
12	---
13	module: win_shell
14	short_description: Execute shell commands on target hosts
15	version_added: 2.2
16	description:
17	     - The C(win_shell) module takes the command name followed by a list of space-delimited arguments.
18	       It is similar to the M(win_command) module, but runs
19	       the command via a shell (defaults to PowerShell) on the target host.
20	     - For non-Windows targets, use the M(shell) module instead.
21	options:
22	  free_form:
23	    description:
24	      - The C(win_shell) module takes a free form command to run.
25	      - There is no parameter actually named 'free form'. See the examples!
26	    type: str
27	    required: yes
28	  creates:
29	    description:
30	      - A path or path filter pattern; when the referenced path exists on the target host, the task will be skipped.
31	    type: path
32	  removes:
33	    description:
34	      - A path or path filter pattern; when the referenced path B(does not) exist on the target host, the task will be skipped.
35	    type: path
36	  chdir:
37	    description:
38	      - Set the specified path as the current working directory before executing a command
39	    type: path
40	  executable:
41	    description:
42	      - Change the shell used to execute the command (eg, C(cmd)).
43	      - The target shell must accept a C(/c) parameter followed by the raw command line to be executed.
44	    type: path
45	  stdin:
46	    description:
47	    - Set the stdin of the command directly to the specified value.
48	    type: str
49	    version_added: '2.5'
50	  no_profile:
51	    description:
52	    - Do not load the user profile before running a command. This is only valid
53	      when using PowerShell as the executable.
54	    type: bool
55	    default: no
56	    version_added: '2.8'
57	  output_encoding_override:
58	    description:
59	    - This option overrides the encoding of stdout/stderr output.
60	    - You can use this option when you need to run a command which ignore the console's codepage.
61	    - You should only need to use this option in very rare circumstances.
62	    - This value can be any valid encoding C(Name) based on the output of C([System.Text.Encoding]::GetEncodings()).
63	      See U(https://docs.microsoft.com/dotnet/api/system.text.encoding.getencodings).
64	    type: str
65	    version_added: '2.10'
66	notes:
67	   -  If you want to run an executable securely and predictably, it may be
68	      better to use the M(win_command) module instead. Best practices when writing
69	      playbooks will follow the trend of using M(win_command) unless C(win_shell) is
70	      explicitly required. When running ad-hoc commands, use your best judgement.
71	   -  WinRM will not return from a command execution until all child processes created have exited.
72	      Thus, it is not possible to use C(win_shell) to spawn long-running child or background processes.
73	      Consider creating a Windows service for managing background processes.
74	seealso:
75	- module: psexec
76	- module: raw
77	- module: script
78	- module: shell
79	- module: win_command
80	- module: win_psexec
81	author:
82	    - Matt Davis (@nitzmahone)
83	'''

12	---
13	module: win_certificate_store
14	version_added: '2.5'
15	short_description: Manages the certificate store
16	description:
17	- Used to import/export and remove certificates and keys from the local
18	  certificate store.
19	- This module is not used to create certificates and will only manage existing
20	  certs as a file or in the store.
21	- It can be used to import PEM, DER, P7B, PKCS12 (PFX) certificates and export
22	  PEM, DER and PKCS12 certificates.
23	options:
24	  state:
25	    description:
26	    - If C(present), will ensure that the certificate at I(path) is imported
27	      into the certificate store specified.
28	    - If C(absent), will ensure that the certificate specified by I(thumbprint)
29	      or the thumbprint of the cert at I(path) is removed from the store
30	      specified.
31	    - If C(exported), will ensure the file at I(path) is a certificate
32	      specified by I(thumbprint).
33	    - When exporting a certificate, if I(path) is a directory then the module
34	      will fail, otherwise the file will be replaced if needed.
35	    type: str
36	    choices: [ absent, exported, present ]
37	    default: present
38	  path:
39	    description:
40	    - The path to a certificate file.
41	    - This is required when I(state) is C(present) or C(exported).
42	    - When I(state) is C(absent) and I(thumbprint) is not specified, the
43	      thumbprint is derived from the certificate at this path.
44	    type: path
45	  thumbprint:
46	    description:
47	    - The thumbprint as a hex string to either export or remove.
48	    - See the examples for how to specify the thumbprint.
49	    type: str
50	  store_name:
51	    description:
52	    - The store name to use when importing a certificate or searching for a
53	      certificate.
54	    - "C(AddressBook): The X.509 certificate store for other users"
55	    - "C(AuthRoot): The X.509 certificate store for third-party certificate authorities (CAs)"
56	    - "C(CertificateAuthority): The X.509 certificate store for intermediate certificate authorities (CAs)"
57	    - "C(Disallowed): The X.509 certificate store for revoked certificates"
58	    - "C(My): The X.509 certificate store for personal certificates"
59	    - "C(Root): The X.509 certificate store for trusted root certificate authorities (CAs)"
60	    - "C(TrustedPeople): The X.509 certificate store for directly trusted people and resources"
61	    - "C(TrustedPublisher): The X.509 certificate store for directly trusted publishers"
62	    type: str
63	    choices:
64	    - AddressBook
65	    - AuthRoot
66	    - CertificateAuthority
67	    - Disallowed
68	    - My
69	    - Root
70	    - TrustedPeople
71	    - TrustedPublisher
72	    default: My
73	  store_location:
74	    description:
75	    - The store location to use when importing a certificate or searching for a
76	      certificate.
77	    choices: [ CurrentUser, LocalMachine ]
78	    default: LocalMachine
79	  password:
80	    description:
81	    - The password of the pkcs12 certificate key.
82	    - This is used when reading a pkcs12 certificate file or the password to
83	      set when C(state=exported) and C(file_type=pkcs12).
84	    - If the pkcs12 file has no password set or no password should be set on
85	      the exported file, do not set this option.
86	    type: str
87	  key_exportable:
88	    description:
89	    - Whether to allow the private key to be exported.
90	    - If C(no), then this module and other process will only be able to export
91	      the certificate and the private key cannot be exported.
92	    - Used when C(state=present) only.
93	    type: bool
94	    default: yes
95	  key_storage:
96	    description:
97	    - Specifies where Windows will store the private key when it is imported.
98	    - When set to C(default), the default option as set by Windows is used, typically C(user).
99	    - When set to C(machine), the key is stored in a path accessible by various
100	      users.
101	    - When set to C(user), the key is stored in a path only accessible by the
102	      current user.
103	    - Used when C(state=present) only and cannot be changed once imported.
104	    - See U(https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.security.cryptography.x509certificates.x509keystorageflags.aspx)
105	      for more details.
106	    type: str
107	    choices: [ default, machine, user ]
108	    default: default
109	  file_type:
110	    description:
111	    - The file type to export the certificate as when C(state=exported).
112	    - C(der) is a binary ASN.1 encoded file.
113	    - C(pem) is a base64 encoded file of a der file in the OpenSSL form.
114	    - C(pkcs12) (also known as pfx) is a binary container that contains both
115	      the certificate and private key unlike the other options.
116	    - When C(pkcs12) is set and the private key is not exportable or accessible
117	      by the current user, it will throw an exception.
118	    type: str
119	    choices: [ der, pem, pkcs12 ]
120	    default: der
121	notes:
122	- Some actions on PKCS12 certificates and keys may fail with the error
123	  C(the specified network password is not correct), either use CredSSP or
124	  Kerberos with credential delegation, or use C(become) to bypass these
125	  restrictions.
126	- The certificates must be located on the Windows host to be set with I(path).
127	- When importing a certificate for usage in IIS, it is generally required
128	  to use the C(machine) key_storage option, as both C(default) and C(user)
129	  will make the private key unreadable to IIS APPPOOL identities and prevent
130	  binding the certificate to the https endpoint.
131	author:
132	- Jordan Borean (@jborean93)
133	'''
134

41	    type: path

52	    - This value can be any valid encoding C(Name) based on the output of C([System.Text.Encoding]::GetEncodings()).
53	      See U(https://docs.microsoft.com/dotnet/api/system.text.encoding.getencodings).
54	    type: str
55	    version_added: '2.10'
56	notes:
57	    - If you want to run a command through a shell (say you are using C(<),
58	      C(>), C(|), etc), you actually want the M(win_shell) module instead. The
59	      C(win_command) module is much more secure as it's not affected by the user's
60	      environment.
61	    - C(creates), C(removes), and C(chdir) can be specified after the command. For instance, if you only want to run a command if a certain file does not

19	description:
20	- Downloads files from HTTP, HTTPS, or FTP to the remote server.

22	- For non-Windows targets, use the M(get_url) module instead.

38	      download the file if it does not exist or the remote file has been

70	        I(url).
71	      - Like C(checksum), this is used to verify the integrity of the remote

11	---
12	module: win_lineinfile
13	short_description: Ensure a particular line is in a file, or replace an existing line using a back-referenced regular expression
14	description:
15	  - This module will search a file for a line, and ensure that it is present or absent.
16	  - This is primarily useful when you want to change a single line in a file only.
17	version_added: "2.0"
18	options:
19	  path:
20	    description:
21	      - The path of the file to modify.
22	      - Note that the Windows path delimiter C(\) must be escaped as C(\\) when the line is double quoted.
23	      - Before Ansible 2.3 this option was only usable as I(dest), I(destfile) and I(name).
24	    type: path
25	    required: yes
26	    aliases: [ dest, destfile, name ]
27	  backup:
28	    description:
29	      - Determine whether a backup should be created.
30	      - When set to C(yes), create a backup file including the timestamp information
31	        so you can get the original file back if you somehow clobbered it incorrectly.
32	    type: bool
33	    default: no
34	  regex:
35	    description:
36	      - The regular expression to look for in every line of the file. For C(state=present), the pattern to replace if found; only the last line found
37	        will be replaced. For C(state=absent), the pattern of the line to remove. Uses .NET compatible regular expressions;
38	        see U(https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/hs600312%28v=vs.110%29.aspx).
39	    aliases: [ "regexp" ]
40	  state:
41	    description:
42	      - Whether the line should be there or not.
43	    type: str
44	    choices: [ absent, present ]
45	    default: present
46	  line:
47	    description:
48	      - Required for C(state=present). The line to insert/replace into the file. If C(backrefs) is set, may contain backreferences that will get
49	        expanded with the C(regexp) capture groups if the regexp matches.
50	      - Be aware that the line is processed first on the controller and thus is dependent on yaml quoting rules. Any double quoted line
51	        will have control characters, such as '\r\n', expanded. To print such characters literally, use single or no quotes.
52	    type: str
53	  backrefs:
54	    description:
55	      - Used with C(state=present). If set, line can contain backreferences (both positional and named) that will get populated if the C(regexp)
56	        matches. This flag changes the operation of the module slightly; C(insertbefore) and C(insertafter) will be ignored, and if the C(regexp)
57	        doesn't match anywhere in the file, the file will be left unchanged.
58	      - If the C(regexp) does match, the last matching line will be replaced by the expanded line parameter.
59	    type: bool
60	    default: no
61	  insertafter:
62	    description:
63	      - Used with C(state=present). If specified, the line will be inserted after the last match of specified regular expression. A special value is
64	        available; C(EOF) for inserting the line at the end of the file.
65	      - If specified regular expression has no matches, EOF will be used instead. May not be used with C(backrefs).
66	    type: str
67	    choices: [ EOF, '*regex*' ]
68	    default: EOF
69	  insertbefore:
70	    description:
71	      - Used with C(state=present). If specified, the line will be inserted before the last match of specified regular expression. A value is available;
72	        C(BOF) for inserting the line at the beginning of the file.
73	      - If specified regular expression has no matches, the line will be inserted at the end of the file. May not be used with C(backrefs).
74	    type: str
75	    choices: [ BOF, '*regex*' ]
76	  create:
77	    description:
78	      - Used with C(state=present). If specified, the file will be created if it does not already exist. By default it will fail if the file is missing.
79	    type: bool
80	    default: no
81	  validate:

83	      - Validation to run before copying into place. Use %s in the command to indicate the current file to validate.
84	      - The command is passed securely so shell features like expansion and pipes won't work.
85	    type: str
86	  encoding:
87	    description:
88	      - Specifies the encoding of the source text file to operate on (and thus what the output encoding will be). The default of C(auto) will cause
89	        the module to auto-detect the encoding of the source file and ensure that the modified file is written with the same encoding.
90	      - An explicit encoding can be passed as a string that is a valid value to pass to the .NET framework System.Text.Encoding.GetEncoding() method -
91	        see U(https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.text.encoding%28v=vs.110%29.aspx).
92	      - This is mostly useful with C(create=yes) if you want to create a new file with a specific encoding. If C(create=yes) is specified without a
93	        specific encoding, the default encoding (UTF-8, no BOM) will be used.
94	    type: str
95	    default: auto
96	  newline:
97	    description:
98	      - Specifies the line separator style to use for the modified file. This defaults to the windows line separator (C(\r\n)). Note that the indicated
99	        line separator will be used for file output regardless of the original line separator that appears in the input file.
100	    type: str

105	seealso:

107	- module: lineinfile

11	---
12	module: win_reboot
13	short_description: Reboot a windows machine
14	description:
15	- Reboot a Windows machine, wait for it to go down, come back up, and respond to commands.
16	- For non-Windows targets, use the M(reboot) module instead.
17	version_added: '2.1'
18	options:
19	  pre_reboot_delay:
20	    description:
21	    - Seconds to wait before reboot. Passed as a parameter to the reboot command.
22	    type: int
23	    default: 2
24	    aliases: [ pre_reboot_delay_sec ]
25	  post_reboot_delay:
26	    description:
27	    - Seconds to wait after the reboot command was successful before attempting to validate the system rebooted successfully.
28	    - This is useful if you want wait for something to settle despite your connection already working.
29	    type: int
30	    default: 0
31	    version_added: '2.4'
32	    aliases: [ post_reboot_delay_sec ]
33	  shutdown_timeout:
34	    description:
35	    - Maximum seconds to wait for shutdown to occur.
36	    - Increase this timeout for very slow hardware, large update applications, etc.
37	    - This option has been removed since Ansible 2.5 as the win_reboot behavior has changed.
38	    type: int
39	    default: 600
40	    aliases: [ shutdown_timeout_sec ]
41	  reboot_timeout:
42	    description:
43	    - Maximum seconds to wait for machine to re-appear on the network and respond to a test command.
44	    - This timeout is evaluated separately for both reboot verification and test command success so maximum clock time is actually twice this value.
45	    type: int
46	    default: 600
47	    aliases: [ reboot_timeout_sec ]
48	  connect_timeout:
49	    description:
50	    - Maximum seconds to wait for a single successful TCP connection to the WinRM endpoint before trying again.
51	    type: int
52	    default: 5
53	    aliases: [ connect_timeout_sec ]
54	  test_command:
55	    description:
56	    - Command to expect success for to determine the machine is ready for management.
57	    type: str
58	    default: whoami
59	  msg:
60	    description:
61	    - Message to display to users.
62	    type: str
63	    default: Reboot initiated by Ansible
64	  boot_time_command:
65	    description:
66	      - Command to run that returns a unique string indicating the last time the system was booted.
67	      - Setting this to a command that has different output each time it is run will cause the task to fail.
68	    type: str
69	    default: '(Get-WmiObject -ClassName Win32_OperatingSystem).LastBootUpTime'
70	    version_added: '2.10'
71	notes:
72	- If a shutdown was already scheduled on the system, C(win_reboot) will abort the scheduled shutdown and enforce its own shutdown.
73	- Beware that when C(win_reboot) returns, the Windows system may not have settled yet and some base services could be in limbo.
74	  This can result in unexpected behavior. Check the examples for ways to mitigate this.
75	- The connection user must have the C(SeRemoteShutdownPrivilege) privilege enabled, see
76	  U(https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/threat-protection/security-policy-settings/force-shutdown-from-a-remote-system)
77	  for more information.
78	seealso:
79	- module: reboot
80	author:
81	- Matt Davis (@nitzmahone)
82	'''
83

19	version_added: '2.0'
20	short_description: Add, change, or remove registry keys and values
21	description:
22	- Add, modify or remove registry keys and values.
23	- More information about the windows registry from Wikipedia
24	  U(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Windows_Registry).
25	options:
26	  path:
27	    description:
28	    - Name of the registry path.
29	    - 'Should be in one of the following registry hives: HKCC, HKCR, HKCU,
30	      HKLM, HKU.'
31	    type: str
32	    required: yes
33	    aliases: [ key ]
34	  name:
35	    description:
36	    - Name of the registry entry in the above C(path) parameters.
37	    - If not provided, or empty then the '(Default)' property for the key will
38	      be used.
39	    type: str
40	    aliases: [ entry, value ]
41	  data:
42	    description:
43	    - Value of the registry entry C(name) in C(path).
44	    - If not specified then the value for the property will be null for the
45	      corresponding C(type).
46	    - Binary and None data should be expressed in a yaml byte array or as comma
47	      separated hex values.
48	    - An easy way to generate this is to run C(regedit.exe) and use the
49	      I(export) option to save the registry values to a file.
50	    - In the exported file, binary value will look like C(hex:be,ef,be,ef), the
51	      C(hex:) prefix is optional.
52	    - DWORD and QWORD values should either be represented as a decimal number
53	      or a hex value.
54	    - Multistring values should be passed in as a list.
55	    - See the examples for more details on how to format this data.
56	    type: str
57	  type:
58	    description:
59	    - The registry value data type.
60	    type: str
61	    choices: [ binary, dword, expandstring, multistring, string, qword ]
62	    default: string
63	    aliases: [ datatype ]
64	  state:
65	    description:
66	    - The state of the registry entry.
67	    type: str
68	    choices: [ absent, present ]
69	    default: present
70	  delete_key:
71	    description:
72	    - When C(state) is 'absent' then this will delete the entire key.
73	    - If C(no) then it will only clear out the '(Default)' property for
74	      that key.
75	    type: bool
76	    default: yes
77	    version_added: '2.4'
78	  hive:
79	    description:
80	    - A path to a hive key like C:\Users\Default\NTUSER.DAT to load in the
81	      registry.
82	    - This hive is loaded under the HKLM:\ANSIBLE key which can then be used
83	      in I(name) like any other path.
84	    - This can be used to load the default user profile registry hive or any
85	      other hive saved as a file.
86	    - Using this function requires the user to have the C(SeRestorePrivilege)
87	      and C(SeBackupPrivilege) privileges enabled.
88	    type: path
89	    version_added: '2.5'
90	notes:
91	- Check-mode C(-C/--check) and diff output C(-D/--diff) are supported, so that you can test every change against the active configuration before
92	  applying changes.
93	- Beware that some registry hives (C(HKEY_USERS) in particular) do not allow to create new registry paths in the root folder.
94	- Since ansible 2.4, when checking if a string registry value has changed, a case-sensitive test is used. Previously the test was case-insensitive.
95	seealso:
96	- module: win_reg_stat
97	- module: win_regmerge
98	author:
99	- Adam Keech (@smadam813)
100	- Josh Ludwig (@joshludwig)
101	- Jordan Borean (@jborean93)

18	       It is similar to the M(win_command) module, but runs
19	       the command via a shell (defaults to PowerShell) on the target host.
20	     - For non-Windows targets, use the M(shell) module instead.
21	options:
22	  free_form:
23	    description:
24	      - The C(win_shell) module takes a free form command to run.
25	      - There is no parameter actually named 'free form'. See the examples!
26	    type: str
27	    required: yes
28	  creates:
29	    description:
30	      - A path or path filter pattern; when the referenced path exists on the target host, the task will be skipped.
31	    type: path
32	  removes:
33	    description:
34	      - A path or path filter pattern; when the referenced path B(does not) exist on the target host, the task will be skipped.
35	    type: path
36	  chdir:
37	    description:
38	      - Set the specified path as the current working directory before executing a command
39	    type: path
40	  executable:
41	    description:
42	      - Change the shell used to execute the command (eg, C(cmd)).
43	      - The target shell must accept a C(/c) parameter followed by the raw command line to be executed.
44	    type: path
45	  stdin:
46	    description:
47	    - Set the stdin of the command directly to the specified value.
48	    type: str
49	    version_added: '2.5'
50	  no_profile:
51	    description:
52	    - Do not load the user profile before running a command. This is only valid
53	      when using PowerShell as the executable.
54	    type: bool
55	    default: no
56	    version_added: '2.8'
57	  output_encoding_override:
58	    description:
59	    - This option overrides the encoding of stdout/stderr output.
60	    - You can use this option when you need to run a command which ignore the console's codepage.
61	    - You should only need to use this option in very rare circumstances.
62	    - This value can be any valid encoding C(Name) based on the output of C([System.Text.Encoding]::GetEncodings()).
63	      See U(https://docs.microsoft.com/dotnet/api/system.text.encoding.getencodings).
64	    type: str
65	    version_added: '2.10'
66	notes:
67	   -  If you want to run an executable securely and predictably, it may be
68	      better to use the M(win_command) module instead. Best practices when writing
69	      playbooks will follow the trend of using M(win_command) unless C(win_shell) is
70	      explicitly required. When running ad-hoc commands, use your best judgement.
71	   -  WinRM will not return from a command execution until all child processes created have exited.
72	      Thus, it is not possible to use C(win_shell) to spawn long-running child or background processes.
73	      Consider creating a Windows service for managing background processes.
74	seealso:
